<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 11 Americans Confirmed Dead in Nairobi Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Eleven Americans are confirmed
dead while another 15 are hospitalized by Friday's bomb blast
rocking the Kenyan capital Nairobi, U.S. embassy spokesman Chris
Scharf told Xinhua Saturday Afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said 14 Kenyans working in the U.S. embassy also
died in the explosion.
</P>
<P>
The injured Americans were expected to be sent to South Africa
and Germany for further treatment, Scharf told Xinhua by phone.
</P>
<P>
"About 40 to 50 FBI (the U.S. Federal Bureau Investigation)
people are expected to arrive in Nairobi tomorrow (Sunday)
morning from Washington" to probe into the blast which according
to the lastest figure, killed more than 100 Kenyans and injured
about 4,200.
</P>
<P>
A few of U.S. FBI experts flew into Nairobi Saturday from
South Africa, according to Scharf.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the state-run Kenya Broadcast Corporation (KBC) said
that a group, self-declared the Islamic Army for the Liberation
of Muslim Holysites, had claimed to be responsible for the bomb
attack.
</P>
<P>
A wounded Eye-witness told Xinhua that just minutes before the
bomb blasted, she saw three persons, with a vehicle, tried to
enter the parking place between the U.S. embassy and the totally
destroyed building.
</P>
<P>
However, Scharf said the U.S. embassy has not received any
information like that.
</P>
<P>
Moments earlier, U.S. Ambassador to Kenya Prudence Bushnell
said the total death toll from the bombing should rise from 108,
the figure given previously by the Kenyan government, to more
than 130 if including the killed Americans and Kenyan employees
in the U.S. embassy.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Foreign Minister Bonaya Godana told foreign envoys in
Nairobi Saturday afternoon that 108 people were killed and 4,149
others injured in Friday's car bombing.
</P>
<P>
"Among our American employees, we have 10 confirmed dead and
five missing... Among our Kenyan employees, we have 14 dead and
109 missing," said Bushnell.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan police said they are probing the bomb blast which
is believed to be a terrorism attack aimed at the Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
