<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Condemns Bomb Attacks in Kenya, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has expressed shock, horror and grief at the August 7
bomb attacks aimed at U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania which
claimed more than 130 lives and injured thousands of others.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued Saturday evening by the President's
Office said that Museveni described the terrorist attacks as
</P>
<P>
"senseless, inhuman and cowardly acts" in a telephone
conversation from Zimbabwe where he is attending a regional
summit.
</P>
<P>
The people of Uganda are horrified by these terrorist attacks
and join their brothers and sisters in Kenya and Tanzania as they
mourn their loved ones, the president said.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the Ugandan government and people, he expressed
his deepest sympathies and condolences to the families of the
deceased and injured, and assured the presidents of Kenya,
Tanzania and the United States of Uganda's solidarity and full
cooperation and assistance in tracking down those behind the bomb
attacks.
</P>
<P>
These attacks underline the importance and urgency of forging
a close-knit cooperation between the three sister east African
countries so that they form an invincible block against such
renegade and barbarous forces, Museveni added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that all right-thinking people of Africa and even
around the globe should work together to ensure that such
atrocities are eliminated from the earth and the perpetrators be
brought to book. 
</P>
</TEXT>
