<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More UK Companies Go Bust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Over 250 companies are going bust
each week in England and Wales of Britain, according to official
government figures.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Trade and Industry said that 3,346 companies
became insolvent in the UK in the second quarter of 1998, an
increase of 4.7 percent from the first quarter of this year or 6.4
percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The number of insolvencies is growing sharply against the
backdrop of a slowing-down of the UK economy. This indicates a
growing recession that is hitting the UK manufacturing sector,
some economists say.
</P>
<P>
Activity in the UK manufacturing sector fell to its lowest rate
for six years in July. According to the Chartered Institute of
Purchasing and Supply, the industry has contracted for the fourth
consecutive month, a factor which has prompted firms to cut
production.
</P>
<P>
Also, the government estimated that around 1.2 percent of
actively trading companies became insolvent in the 12 months to
July 1998. Individual insolvencies rose to 6,214, an increase of
2.2 percent from the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
However, not all companies that call in the receiver are closed
down. Some can be rescued and sold as a going business, according
to local media reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
