<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Controls Key Positions in  Mazar-i-Sharif </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia,
which marched into Mazar-i-Sharif Saturday, have secured key
positions in the city including the airport, government buildings
and road junctions.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia are now trying to flush out remaining
opposition troops in the city in a bid to take full control of the
stronghold of the anti-Taliban Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban launched a major attack against Mazar-i-Sharif
Saturday morning and stormed into the city after breaking through
the opposition defenses.
</P>
<P>
Taliban sources from Mazar-i-Sharif said that a total of 5, 000
Taliban troops took part in Saturday's fighting which started from
Daulatabad area, about 40 kilometers north of the city. The
Taliban entered the city after midday following hours of intense
fighting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to media reports reaching here from
Mazar-i-Sharif Saturday afternoon the bulk of opposition forces
were fleeing south to the mountainous central massif of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Iranian News Agency (IRNA) said that
Mazar-i-Sharif, the only major Afghan city which was beyond the
Taliban's control, has been totally over-run by the Taliban
militia.
</P>
<P>
"The city fell moments ago and repeated explosions are being
heard in the city," IRNA said.
</P>
<P>
"There are only pockets of resistance, alliance officials have
left the town and people too are fleeing," it said, adding that
"parts of Mazar-i-Sharif are now burning and many homes have been
destroyed."
</P>
<P>
Taliban sources said that they used jet planes, conducting air
raids against the military targets of the Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
Relief agencies have already withdrawn from the city in fear of
the fighting after the Taliban captured Shiberghan, capital of
Jawzjan province last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time the Taliban have entered Mazar-i-Sharif.
The Taliban seized control of the city in May 1997 after joining
ranks with Abdul Malik, a former ally of opposition warlord Abdul
Rashid Dostam, who allowed them to enter the stronghold.
</P>
<P>
However, when a deal over power sharing broke down, Malik
returned to the fold of the anti-Taliban Northern Alliance to
inflict brutal killings on at least 2,500 Taliban soldiers trapped
in the north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
