<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 African Leaders Call for End to Congo War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Seven African Leaders including
President Laurent Kabila of Democratic Congo (DRC) Saturday
called for an end to the war in DRC and set up a panel to probe
charges that Rwanda and Uganda are backing the rebels there.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the end of a six-hour meeting in the Victoria
Falls, a resort town on Zimbabwe's northern border, host
President Robert Mugabe told a news conference that all the
delegates have agreed the on-going war in DRC must end and urged
those involved to lay down their arms.
</P>
<P>
"We want the fighting to stop and the situation to go back to
normalcy," Zambia News Agency ZANA quoted Mugabe as saying.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released after the meeting, the seven
presidents said they have established a four-nation committee,
comprising Zambia, Zimbabwe, Namibia and Tanzania, to probe all
the allegations, including that Rwanda and Uganda are involved in
the week-long military rebellion in the former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"We will investigate all the allegations. But for us the
important thing is that the fighting is to put to an end," Mugabe
said.
</P>
<P>
The regional summit hosted by Mugabe attracted DRC's Kabila,
Zambia's Frederick Chiluba, Rwanda's Pasteur Bizimingu, Uganda's
Yoweri Museveni, Tanzania's Benjamin Mkapa and Namibia's Sam
Nujoma.
</P>
<P>
The DRC authorities have been accusing Rwanda and Uganda of
backing the week-long rebellion by the country's ethic Tutsi
Banyamulenge community aiming at toppling Kabila's new
government, which are denied by the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
