<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Millions of Chinese Continue to Fight Floods (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Millions of local residents along
the raging Yangtze River today continued to be busy protecting
their homes from devastating floods.
</P>
<P>
In the middle reaches of the Yangtze River, the water level at
the Jingjiang section, in central China's Hubei province, has kept
above the previous record set in 1954 and local officials have
made preparations for a possible diversion by blowing up the dykes
in the Gong'an county.
</P>
<P>
More than 300,000 residents have been working all day to tackle
emergency cases along the Jingjiang dykes, while in the downstream
city of Wuhan, seven million residents are preparing for a new
flood crest that has been formed because of torrential rains in
recent days.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the fourth flood crest on the Yangtze
River passed through the city of Yichang, also in Hubei, early
this morning. Fortunately, the city's 267 km of embankments stood
to the trial and remained intact.
</P>
<P>
Water levels at Yichang went down slowly today, and by 5:00
p.m. today, they were down to 53.21 m., down 0.7 m. from the
highest level, and the flow rate was down to 56,600 cu.m. per
second, down 4,900 cu.m. from the highest rate.
</P>
<P>
However, in the downstream provinces of Hunan and Jiangxi,
situation became even tougher. In Hunan's Dongting Lake, water
level rose to 35.54 metres at the Chenglingji Measuring Point,
0.23 metres higher than the historical record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
