<HEADLINE> Millions of Chinese Continue to Fight Floods(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At present, nearly two million residents and 15,000 soldiers
have been stationed in the Dongting Lake area to safeguard the
weakened dykes and deal with emergency cases.
</P>
<P>
To date, the Jiangxi province has been confronted with the
severest challenge, as the levee in the industrial city of
Jiujiang partially collapsed Friday afternoon, with water gushing
in nearly one-seventh of the city area.
</P>
<P>
By 24:00 tonight, the breach has not been plugged yet although
painstaking efforts have been made. Flood-control experts and a
special contingent of the army have used some of the most advanced
anti-flood methods and expected to bring the situation under
control tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
According to Shu Shengyou, Governor of Jiangxi province, no
casualties have so far been reported in Jiujiang and life has
been by and large normal in urban Jiujiang.
</P>
<P>
So far, supplies of water, electricity and daily necessities
have been adequate as usual in the city.
</P>
<P>
In the lower reaches of the Yangtze River, the provinces of
Anhui and Jiangsu have both been in the state of flood emergency
and about two million people and soldiers have been mobilized to
safeguard the dykes.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, more than 2,000 people have died
in the floods for the past two months and the death toll is still
on the rise. About 240 million people, a fifth of the total
population, have been affected by the floods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
