<HEADLINE> 28 Egyptian Militants Sentenced to Prison Terms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-eight Egyptian Muslim
militants who were found guilty of armed robbery were sentenced to
prison terms Saturday, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-seven men were put on trial Saturday at the State
Supreme Security Court on charges of subversion, armed robbery,
joining the militant Al Gamaa Al Islamiya (Islamic Group) and
possessing weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Group is Egypt's largest militant rebel faction,
which has been waging a violent campaign against the secular
government since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six of the defendants were sentenced to five to 15 years
in jail, with hard labor.
</P>
<P>
Another two, including a boy aged 15, will serve three years
behind bars. The remaining nine were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
The accused were arrested in 1995, suspected of involvement in
a series of armed robbery of jewelry stores owned by Coptic
Christians on the suburbs of Cairo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
