<DOCNO> XIE19980809.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian FM Visits Iran on Jerusalem Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Foreign Minister Jawad
Anani said Muslim countries should, if necessary, consider even a
military option to prevent Israel's Judaizing Jerusalem, the
official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark upon arrival in Tehran Saturday afternoon to
begin a three-day visit to discuss with Iranian officials regional
and international issues, particularly Israel's Jerusalem
expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
It sounds a little bit unusual for a Jordanian official to
highlight such an option. Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Anani said that Jerusalem concerns every Muslim state, and the
Islamic world should show appropriate reaction to the Israeli
conspiracy to Judaize the holy city.
</P>
<P>
As members of the Jerusalem Committee of the Organization of
the Islamic Countries (OIC), Iran and Jordan, which have discussed
the issue at the meeting of OIC foreign ministers in Morocco on
July 30, need further discussion, he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel, in the midst of an impasse of the Mideast peace
process, approved a plan on June 21 to extend Jerusalem's
authority to eight Jewish settlements in the West Bank, setting
off a storm of criticism inside and outside Israel.
</P>
<P>
Anani said that his talks with Iranian officials will also
cover other issues pertaining to the Islamic world, the Mideast
peace process, and ways to enhance bilateral cooperation in
economy, tourism and culture.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi, who greeted
Anani at the Mehrabad International Airport, said the visit will
serve to further develop bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Iran broke off diplomatic ties during the 1980-88
Iran-Iraq war because of Jordan's siding with Iraq, but resumed
relations after the conflict ended.
</P>
<P>
The atmosphere has grown warmer since Mohammad Khatami became
Iran's president in May 1997, who tried to mend fences between
Iran and Arab states, including Jordan.
</P>
<P>
However, the two still disagree on the Mideast peace process.
Jordan is eager to play a constructive role in the process while
Iran firmly opposes to any peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Anani is scheduled to hold talks with Khatami
and Majlis Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
