<DOCNO> XIE19980809.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Says Angolan Visit Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- United Nations envoy Lakhdar
Brahimi said here Saturday that his eight-day visit to Angola has
achieved positive results.
</P>
<P>
The impact of the visit will be felt when talks between the
Angolan government and the opposition National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) are resumed in the next few days,
and the crisis to the peace process recedes, he told a press
conference here before concluding his visit.
</P>
<P>
During his visit in Angola, Brahimi has forwarded Annan's
letters to Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos and UNITA
chairman Jonas Savimbi. He also met with the troika missions of
United States, Russia and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Isaias Samakuva, head of UNITA delegation to the
joint committee of the Angola peace process, who left two months
ago, has returned to Luanda.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, United Nations Secretary-General Kofo Annan has
appointed Issa Diallo as U.N. special representative to Angola
after his predecessor Blondin Beye died in a plane crash on June
26.
</P>
<P>
However, Brahimi believed the situation in Angola is still
worrying. He called on the international community to continue
with its utmost efforts to bring the peace process back on its
course.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi arrived here on July 31 to start his visit aimed at
restoring the mutual trust between the Angolan government and
UNITA so as to ensure the unaccomplished tasks of the 1994 Lusaka
peace accord are completed.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy will also visit Namibia, South Africa, Zimbabwe
and Zambia to persuade leaders of the four countries to lend
their further support to the peace process in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The current crisis facing Angola is the worst since 1994 when
the two warring sides signed a peace agreement in Lusaka, Zambia,
ending the 19-year civil war, due to UNITA's failure to hand over
the four central cities under its control and its snatching over
of more cities which had already been under the government
control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
