<HEADLINE> PLC Postpones Vote on New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian Legislative
Council (PLC) decided Saturday to postpone its vote on the new
cabinet till Sunday, said a senior Palestinian official in
Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
The legislature decided to give more time to its members to
study the lineup of the new cabinet presented by Chairman Yasser
Arafat of the Palestinian National Authority, the official added.
</P>
<P>
Arafat sent the list of the reshuffled cabinet to the PLC for
approval Wednesday. The former cabinet resigned after being
charged of corruption and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
However, the reshuffle was a far cry from an expected
overhaul. Not only did Arafat keep almost all the old faces, he
also introduced three more ministries and 10 new ministers,
bringing the total number of ministers, ministers of state and
ministers with or without portfolios to 30.
</P>
<P>
The new ministries are Environment, Parliamentary Affairs and
Prisoners Affairs.
</P>
<P>
However, former Higher Education Minister Hanan Ashrawi
rejected the new post and quited the cabinet on Thursday. She
criticized that the shakeup failed to send a strong message
against corruption and the new cabinet was incapable of dealing
with political pressures imposed on Palestinians by the current
Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawai also said that the new cabinet is unprofessional and
disunited.
</P>
<P>
Adbul Jawad Saleh, the former agriculture minister and a
minister without portfolio in the new lineup, also resigned on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has urged all lawmakers, particularly those from the his
Fatah faction, to vote in favor of the new cabinet, the official
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
