<HEADLINE> Congo Govt Troops Hit Back in West: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- President Laurent Kabila have
sent troops to counter-attack rebels in the western ports near
the Atlantic Ocean, a report reaching here quoted an Interior
Ministry official as saying in Kinshasa Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Reinforcements had been sent to the oil town of Muanda by air
and road, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have begun a counter-attack at Muanda, contrary to what is
being said. The town has not fallen. What I know is that we are
continuing to send reinforcements on the ground," the official
who refused to be named, said.
</P>
<P>
"Planes carrying our troops are landing on the airfield at
Muanda so how can anyone say that at the same time the town is in
the hands of the aggressors?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Kabila admitted Thursday that the eastern towns of Goma and
Bukavu were in rebel hands.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers from Democratic Congo's ethnic Tutsi Banyamulenge
community, whose 1996 revolt against late dictator Mobutu Sese
Seko grew into the bush war that brought Kabila to power,
launched the latest rebellion on August 2 in the eastern town of
Goma.
</P>
<P>
The rebels claimed Friday that their forces were advancing on
several fronts, including the port of Matadi, on the western
corridor cut through to the Atlantic by the Congo river, and the
southern town of Kalemie, gateway to copper-rich Shaba province.
</P>
<P>
Kabila accuses Rwanda, whose Tutsi-dominated army helped send
him to power, and Uganda of fomenting the revolt and of sending
troops to fight in Congo (K). Both countries denied involving in
the rebellion inside the central African nation.
</P>
<P>
Six African heads of state were meeting in crisis talks in
Zimbabwe to find ways of ending the conflict in Congo. 
</P>
