<HEADLINE> Lebanon, Iraq to Move toward Better Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 8 (Xinhua) -- In a significant move toward
improving relations, Lebanon and Iraq agreed that each will send a
civil servant to the other's capital, a Foreign Ministry source
said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This is seen as an important step since their diplomatic
relations were severed following the assassination of an Iraqi
opposition figure, Taleb Suhail al-Tamimi, in Beirut in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi diplomats were then convicted of murdering Tamimi and
expelled.
</P>
<P>
The source said the decision to exchange civil servant was made
after consultations between Lebanese Foreign Minister Fares Boueiz
and his Iraqi counterpart Mohammed Said al-Sahhaf.
</P>
<P>
The Voice of the People radio reported the Lebanese civil
servant will have no diplomatic status and his appointment was
believed desirable by Lebanese economic organizations that have
signed contracts with Iraq under the U.N. oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
The civil servant at the Lebanese embassy in Baghdad will be
charged of facilitating customs formalities in trade between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The source said the move does not constitute a step towards a
restoration of diplomatic ties with Baghdad, though Iraq has
repeatedly made such a demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
