<HEADLINE> 132 Dead, 4,257 Injured in Nairobi Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The latest figure for the bomb
blast in downtown Nairobi, capital of Kenya, is 132 people dead,
including 11 Americans, and 4,257 injured, a government spokesman
said Saturday evening here at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
At least 11 corpses have been found from the rubble of the
bomb blast since Saturday afternoon, in addition to two retrieved
alive, rescuers told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The rescue workers have managed to continuously communicate by
a microphone with the two trapped people -- one is in a lift,
another one behind a thick concrete wall, Avi Regev, the
spokesman for the Israeli rescue team, said at 8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
As many as 180 soldiers from the Israeli Defense Force flew
into Nairobi from Israel at 2:00 p.m. local time and had started
to work in the rubble by 4:00 p.m., Regev said, adding that they
will work in shifts all night.
</P>
<P>
Now the rescuers planned to prop up some pillars to sustain
the wall while trying to provide oxygen to the trapped with the
aid of some special equipment, Regev said.
</P>
<P>
The workers will then send special-trained dogs, loaded with
foods for survival, inside the rubble to reach people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, the outsiders will keep talking with the
trapped for psychological support.
</P>
<P>
"The work goes slow, because we have to work very patient and
very careful," he stressed, noting that even small negligence may
cause the falling of stones, resulting in the death of not only
the trapped but also the rescuers.
</P>
<P>
"We are still searching for more people," he said, adding that
he believed more people are still inside the debris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
