Amr Moussa on the deadlocked Mideast peace process and the latest
Iraq-U.N. standoff.
</P>
<P>
Moussa, who paid a unscheduled visit to Saudi Arabia Saturday,
briefed the prince on the efforts made by Egypt and France to
revive the peace process, the Kuwait News Agency Kuna reported.
</P>
<P>
In May, Egypt and France put forward an initiative calling for
an international conference to reactivate the Mideast peace
process, which has been deadlocked due to Israel's intransigency.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed the Iraq-U.N. standoff after
Iraq decided Tuesday to suspend cooperation with the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) and International Atomic Energy Agency. The
two bodies are carrying out arms inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi decision came after talks between its Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz and UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler broke down
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Both Moussa and Saud stressed the need for Iraq to comply with
all relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed sanctions on Iraq after its invasion of
Kuwait, and began search for weapons of mass destruction in Iraq
soon after the 1991 Gulf War brought Iraq to its defeat.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions will not be lifted until the UNSCOM certifies
that Iraq has eliminated all banned weapons. 
</P>
