<HEADLINE> Turkey Urges Stop of Foreign Support in Afghan War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkey on Saturday called for a
stop of foreign aid of weapons and personnel to any of the warring
fractions in Afghanistan to help end the devastating civil war.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Foreign Ministry made the call in a statement. It
said Turkey is gravely concerned that the worsening situation in
Afghanistan can cause further bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
Turkey hoped the conflicting sides will return to the
negotiating table and finally achieve a ceasefire soon, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that "Turkey believes that a lasting peace in
Afghanistan could only be provided with the establishment of a
government where all groups will be represented."
</P>
<P>
Ankara also expresses concerns over human rights violations in
Afghanistan against to women and children.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey believes that Taliban militia should provide facilities
to the continuation of the efforts of international aid
organizations to bring humanitarian aid to Afghanistan under
severe conditions," the statement stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban Saturday captured the last major city of
Mazar-e-Sharif, dealing a heavy blow to its rival Northern
Alliance, headed by ousted President Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, a student militia believed to be supported by
Pakistan, has won control over more than two thirds of country
after driving Rabbani's government out of the capital Kabul in
September 1996.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Taliban and the Northern Alliance have been
deadlocked since May and fightings have since flared up again.
</P>
</TEXT>
