<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen Cypriot firefighters
left Saturday for Greece to help battle raging forest fires there,
including a wall of flames that are closing in on the ancient site
of the Olympic games.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made during a Council of Ministers' meeting
Friday, Cypriot government sources said.
</P>
<P>
Greek Justice and Public Order Minister George Romeos has
thanked the Cypriot government for its practical help.
</P>
<P>
Hot weather and lack of rain have made easy the spread of
forest fire and rendered it very difficulty to put out the flames,
which threatened to turn part of the country into a furnace.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Turkish Cypriot-controlled
north and Greek Cypriot-dominated south since 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took the north third of Cyprus in the wake
of abortive coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greece has since been a strong supporter of the Greek
Cypriot-dominated Cypriot government and the two governments have
kept close ties.
</P>
<P>
So far, Italy and France have sent firefighting aircraft and
personnel to Greece. 
