<HEADLINE> Cyprus Says Not to Bow to Threats on Missile Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Defense Minister
Yiannakis Omirou said Saturday that his government will not give
in to pressures and threats over the planned purchase of Russian
missiles.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to new recruits to the National Guard at a Larnaca
army camp, Omirou said his government's position and that of
pro-government political parties are well known, and that is "We
will never operate under blackmail or pressure."
</P>
<P>
Omirou called on all countries concerned about security and
stability in the region to exercise pressure on Turkey instead of
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"We are a power of peace, stability, security and cooperation
in the region and those third parties who want to create the
impression that we are part of a game of tension will be proved
wrong," he said.
</P>
<P>
Omirou said the National Guard will safeguard peace, and "if we
are provoked we will defend the rights of Cypriot Hellenism until
the end."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus clinched a deal with Russia early last year to buy the
surface-to-air S-300 missile system, which is due to be delivered
and deployed later this year.
</P>
<P>
This is seen as a threat by Turkish Cypriots in northern Cyprus
and Turkey, which has threatened pre-emptive strike if the
missiles are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Some foreign governments, especially the U.S. and Britain,
have also voiced opposition to Cyprus' decision.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into Turkish Cypriot-controlled
north and Greek Cypriot-dominated south since 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the north third of the island in
the wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, the Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a breakaway
state in northern Cyprus, which is recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored peace talks toward a solution to the
long-running Cyprus issue broke down last summer after the Turkish
Cypriots walked out of the negotiations to protest against a
European Union decision to start membership talks with Cyprus, not
their supporter Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
