<HEADLINE> One Comes out of Nairobi Bomb Rubble Alive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- A Kenyan man trapped in the
rubble of Friday's bomb blast got out to safety Saturday night
after one and half days of tense work by rescuers.
</P>
<P>
A huge car bomb explosion brought down the whole building on
the rear of the U.S. embassy, crashing down around the man who is
identified as Gatili Nganga.
</P>
<P>
The man was said at his middle age and was injured quite
seriously. At least one more person was still alive in the
debris.
</P>
<P>
The latest government figure for the bomb blast is 132 people
dead, including 11 Americans, and 4,257 injured.
</P>
<P>
At least 11 corpses have been found from the rubble of the
bomb blast since 4:00 p.m. local time, rescuers told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The rescue workers had managed to communicate continuously by
a microphone with Nganga and the other trapped person, said Avi
Regev, the spokesman for the Israeli rescue team which flew in
earlier Saturday.
</P>
<P>
As many as 180 soldiers from the Israeli Defense Force flew
into Nairobi from Israel at 2:00 p.m. local time and had started
to work in the rubble by 4:00 p.m., Regev said, adding that they
will work in shifts all night.
</P>
<P>
French, American and British aid teams are expected to come in
as from Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The rescuers first planned to prop up some pillars to sustain
the wall while trying to provide oxygen to the trapped with the
aid of some special equipment, Regev said.
</P>
<P>
"The work goes slow, because we have to work very patient and
very careful," he stressed, noting that even small negligence may
cause the falling of stones, resulting in the death of not only
the trapped but also the rescuers.
</P>
<P>
"We are still searching for more people," he said, adding that
he believed more people are still inside the debris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
