<HEADLINE> World Condoles with Tanzania on Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 8 (Xinhua) - World leaders have begun
pouring messages of condolences to Tanzania upon its suffering
during a powerful car-bomb attack at the United States Embassy on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The incident has claimed nine lives and wounded at least 70
civilians as of Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs said U.S.
President Bill Clinton personally telephoned Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa, expressing his deep condolence upon the bombing.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who was at Victoria Falls in Zimbabwe, agreed with
Clinton to work closely in apprehending the terrorists and bring
them to justice.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa was attending a summit for heads of state from Namibia,
Rwanda, Uganda, Zimbabwe, Zambia and the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) on the volatile situation in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
In his message of condolence, Australian Prime Minister John
Howard said his country was committed to cooperating in any way
with its allies to undercover those behind the bombing.
</P>
<P>
"On behalf of all Australians, I offer our heartfelt
condolence to the families of those who have been killed or
injured," said Howard.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa also received messages from Queen Elizabeth of Britain,
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi of Japan, President Hosni Mubarak of
Egypt, President Yasser Arafat of the State of Palestine,
President Negaso Gidada and Prime Minister Meles Zenawi of
Ethiopia and Klaus Kinkel, the Foreign Minister of Germany.
</P>
<P>
The leaders all condemned the bombing as cowardly and
unjustified, expressing solidarity with Tanzania and offered to
do whatever possible in dealing with the present situation and
investigating the incident.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Minister for Foreign Affairs and International
Cooperation, Jakaya Kikwete, also received messages of condolence
from his counterparts from the Republic of Korea, Norway, Japan,
Britain and the Netherlands. 
