<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-08 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Not to Release More Water to Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has no intention to
increase Euphrates water supply to Syria to solve their
long-running water row, the Turkish Daily News reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The flow of more water to Syria is the natural result of the
accelerated electricity generation at Turkey's Ataturk Dam over
the Euphrates River, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
According to Turkey's State Water Affairs Institution, an
average of 989.4 cubic Euphrates water was released to Syria every
second in the first seven months in 1998, much higher than the 500
cubic meters per second limit Ankara lets flow to Syria from its
Ataturk Dam.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a unnamed expert from the institution as
saying that "in order to produce more electricity, more water is
required," and this does not mean Turkey has soften its stance on
its water dispute with Syria.
</P>
<P>
The water distribution of the Euphrates, which originates in
Turkey and flows toward Syria and Iraq, has been an entrenched
dispute among the three countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Syria signed a protocol in 1987, under which Turkey
got 500 cubic meters of Euphrates water a second and the two were
supposed to reach a new agreement on a new, higher Syrian share
once the Ataturk Dam was completed.
</P>
<P>
The dam was finished in 1991 but no new agreement has been
hammered out to date because their strained relations have prevent
a dialog.
</P>
<P>
Turkey accuses Syria of sheltering leader of its outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party and (PKK) Abdullah Ocalan, and of providing
support for the PKK, which has been fighting a 14-year war for
independence in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Syria and Iraq have been lobbying the Arab world to
pressure Turkey to release more water to them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
