<HEADLINE> Iranians Detained in Taliban-Captured Afghan City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranians in the Afghan city of
Mazar-e-Sharif captured by the Taliban militia Saturday have been
detained, the Iranian official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats in the Iranian consulate in the city and an IRNA
correspondent, have all been taken into custody, said the people,
who introduced themselves as Taliban militiamen in answering a
call to the consulate.
</P>
<P>
The IRNA report did not mention how many Iranians remained in
the consulate in the city when it captured by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Early Saturday morning, the Taliban captured Mazar-e-Sharif,
the main stronghold of the Northern Alliance headed by ousted
Afghan President Burhanuddin Rabbani, dealing a severe blow to its
rival.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, a student militia believed to be support by
Pakistan, drove Rabbani's government out of the capital Kabul in
September 1996 and has won control over more than two thirds of
the country.
</P>
<P>
It has since imposed a strict form of Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
U.N.-sponsored peace talks between Taliban and the Northern
Alliance broke down in May and the Taliban resumed attack on area
under the alliance's control.
</P>
<P>
Iran, which supports the Northern Alliance, has withdrawn its
ambassador to Afghanistan early this week.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi has
said Tehran held Pakistan and the Taliban responsible for the
safety of Iranian diplomats in Mazar-e-Sharif. 
</P>
</TEXT>
