<HEADLINE> No Military Solution to Afghan Crisis: Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said here Saturday that the Afghan crisis has no military
solution and can only be settled through political means.
</P>
<P>
It was Iran's first reaction to the fall of Mazar-e-Sharif, the
main stronghold of the Northern Alliance headed by Afghan
President Burhanuddin Rabbani, to the hands of the Afghan Taliban
militia Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
Receiving Jordanian Foreign Minister Jawad al-Anani at the
airport, Kharrazi said the fact is that the Taliban have attained
successes in Afghanistan with support from certain foreign
governments.
</P>
<P>
Iran holds Pakistan and the Taliban responsible for the safety
of Iranian diplomats in Mazar-e-Sharif, the official news agency
IRNA quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, a student militia believed to have the support of
Pakistan, has won control over more than two thirds of Afghanistan
and since imposed a strict form of Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
Tehran has been supporting the Northern Alliance, which
suffered a heavy blow with Taliban's seizure of Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
However, Kharrazi said, in case of Taliban's control of entire
Afghanistan, the ethnic minorities should continue to survive and
are entitled to a share in the destiny of their country.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi has voiced Tehran's strong opposition to any foreign
military intervention in Afghanistan on Friday.
</P>
<P>
He called on all countries, including Afghanistan's neighbors,
to try to persuade the belligerent parties to engage in serious
negotiation.
</P>
<P>
He warned that Iran cannot allow security of this sensitive
region to be played with and become a tool of others for their
ambitions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
