- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 9 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
Sunday sent a letter of condolence to victims of Friday's bomb
blast in Kenyan capital, reported the state-run Kenya News Agency.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Annan said he was shocked by the bomb raid aimed
at the U.S. embassy in downtown Nairobi. The blast killed at least
155 people and injured nearly 5,000.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the United Nations will provide assistance to help
the east African country deal with the tragedy, the report noted.
