<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Urged to Increase Exports to Cut Deficit With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh should increase its
exports to India by further devaluing its currency, stopping
smuggling and seeking reductions in tariff and non-tariff
barriers, so as to narrow down its huge trade gap with its giant
neighbor, an expert said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
And more Indian investments in Bangladesh should be encouraged,
and SAPTA (South Asian Preferential Trading Arrangement) made more
operational and meaningful, Dr Kabir Hassan, an associate
professor of a U.S. university and a research fellow of American
Institute of Bangladesh Studies told a seminar here on
"Indo-Bangla Trade."
</P>
<P>
The seminar was organized by the Center for Development and
Research of Bangladesh and the Federation of Bangladesh Chambers
of Commerce and Industry (FBCCI).
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has run a huge deficit of at least 2 billion U.S.
dollars in terms of both formal and informal cross-border trade
with India, according to FBCCI President Yussuf Abdullah Harun.
</P>
<P>
Over 25 percent of Bangladesh's total imports came from India
which has only 0.5 percent of its imports from Bangladesh, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh exports mainly chemical and allied products to India
and imports textile and textile-related raw materials from that
country.
</P>
<P>
Joint-venture projects in such fields as agro-processing, light
industries, coal, telecommunications, power and tourism under
buy-back arrangements, suppliers credit from India under easy
terms, and joint development of infrastructure might contribute to
offsetting the current trade imbalance, the FBCCI chief said.
</P>
<P>
"The huge trade imbalance is a result of inappropriate
exchange-rate policy on behalf of Bangladesh," Dr Hassan observed.
The international inconvertibility of the currencies of SAARC
(South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation) members
countries was hindering trade among them, he added.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Secretary Sayed Alamgir Farrouk Chowdhury urged
Bangladeshi businessmen to "shift their focus of attention from
the European and American countries to India and create market
through persuasion and improvement of standard of local products."
The U.S. is now the largest trading partner of Bangladesh,
followed by Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
