<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Inspects Yangtze River Embankment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINGZHOU, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji today
urged all provinces along the Yangtze River to remain highly
vigilant and go all out in fighting the floods to ensure the
safety of the main Yangtze River embankment.
</P>
<P>
Zhu spoke during an inspection tour of the embankment at
Jingzhou City in central China's Hubei Province as millions of
people, including soldiers, are fighting the rampaging floods,
China's most severe since 1954.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of President Jiang Zemin, the Central Committee of
the Communist Party of China and the State Council, Zhu extended
warm regards and sincere thanks to flood-fighters.
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of tens of thousands of soldiers for their
remarkable role in fighting the floods. The soldiers have always
rushed to the rescue in places of danger, he said, adding that it
demonstrates once again that the People's Liberation Army is
the Chinese people's own army.
</P>
<P>
At present, Zhu said, the flood situation is very serious on
the Yangtze River. There is a high possibility of cave-ins and
crumbling along the main river dikes because of the long soaking
period. In addition, more rainfall and new flood crests are
expected to come from the upper reaches of the Yangtze, Zhu
said.
</P>
<P>
He urged people fighting the floods to surmount all
difficulties and persevere to the end.
</P>
<P>
Leadership at all levels should organize patrols along the
river dikes, put their emphasis on key river sections, and send
more troops, armed police and public security officers if
necessary, he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu urged local governments to place people's lives above all,
telling them to move the people to safer places, take good care of
their daily lives and send more medical teams to flood-afflicted
areas.
</P>
<P>
In the past two days, Zhu toured the Jingjiang, Shishou and
Honghu sections, the most dangerous parts of the Yangtze, where he
listened to the reports of local government officials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
