<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's Zamyad Company will export a total of 1,000
minibuses and lorries to Yemen, the Iran News daily reported on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of 25 minibuses and 25 lorries are to be
shipped to Yemen in the day.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The National Iranian Oil Company has postponed an
international oil tender worth 8 billion U.S. dollars till
September 1-3, a month later than scheduled, the Iran News said on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Reasons for the delay were unknown, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
The tender based on buyback includes 21 gas and oil projects.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH -- The World Bank has said that financial aids granted
by donor countries to the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
dropped sharply in 1997 compared with 1996, the Arabic-language Al
Hayat daily reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A report issued last week by the resident mission of the bank
in Palestine said the PNA received 210 million dollars last year,
160 million dollars less than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- While the currencies of some major Mideast countries
showed a depreciation trend against the U.S. dollar in the last
few years, the Egyptian pound has remained stable, Egypt's Middle
East News Agency (MENA) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
An International Monetary Fund (IMF) report obtained by MENA
said the exchange rate of the Egyptian currency was 3.3880 pounds
to the U.S. dollar in the end of last May, compared with 3.3910 in
1994.
</P>
<P>
This happened when the exchange rates to the dollar dipped in
Sudan, Israel, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Morocco and Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese pound slumped to its lowest record of 1,819.70
pounds to the dollar at the end of last April compared with 6.96
in 1991 and 289.61 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli shekel also fell to 3.6560 shekels to the dollar
last May compared with 2.2830 at the end of 1991 and 3.4494 in
1997, the IMF said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
