<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Endeavors to Increase Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Minister of Petroleum
Albina Assis has said the country will work hard to increase oil
production to use the revenue to develop agriculture and
industry.
</P>
<P>
The country cannot create a large number of jobs and produce
more national products without the development of agriculture and
industry, she said in a speech carried by Sunday's Angola Daily.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, she said, Angola's daily oil production is 735,000
barrels. The number will grow to a daily one million barrels in
the next century with the discovery of a serious of new oil
fields with rich reserves, she added.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Assis said, 53 percent of the country's oil
production comes from Cabinda Province, an enclave to the north
of Angola. The rest is mostly offshore oil from the Bay of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The minister predicted that the oil production will increase
remarkably between the year 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Eld Petroleum Corporation of France discovered three big
oil fields near Luanda last year, with oil reserves being 735
million barrels, 660 million barrels and 700 million barrels
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Regarding problems now facing the oil industry, she said, the
country's relevant legislature is too rigid and simple, and
cannot fit the current situation. He called for the reform of
the government in order to attract more foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the minsiter noted, since the monthly government
expenditure on fuel subsidy is as much as two million U.S.
Dollars, the priority should be given to the reduction of the
subsidy so that more capital will be used on re-investment in the
state-owned petroleum company, the Sonangol, and the
rehabilitation of its infrastructure.  
</P>
</TEXT>
