<HEADLINE> Nigerian Port Records Sharp Rise in Cargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The Apapa Port of Nigeria handled
a record of 3.36 million tons of cargoes in the first half of
this year, about 80 percent higher than the target of 1.84
million tons projected for the period.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics released by Nigerian Ports Authority show
that it also represents a significant improvement of 1.5 million
tons compared to 1.86 million tons of the cargoes in the same
period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Of the 3.36 million tons, 3.24 million tons of cargoes were
imported as against 1.7 million tons in the same period of last
year while 120,006 tons were cleared as exports compared to the
1997 figure of 159,265 tons.
</P>
<P>
Maritime operators were quoted as attributed the improved
activities at the port, one of the major ports of Nigeria, to the
increased import of fertilizer and petroleum products by the
Federal Government.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total 3.24 million tons of imported cargoes, both
dry and liquid bulk accounted for 918,671 tons and 1.7 million
tons respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
