<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official: No New Meetings With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian side has
decided not to continue direct talks with Israel due to its
insincerity over redeployment issue, a senior Palestinian official
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erekat announced the decision
in an interview with the Voice of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said "we do not want to get the peace process into mere
talks and giving Israel additional miles or more chances since we
hope for reaching an implementation of agreements and not only to
talk about peace without adopting practical measures."
</P>
<P>
Direct talks between the Palestinians and Israel resumed July
19 after a lapse of 16 months.
</P>
<P>
But the talks have achieved little progress because of the big
gap between the two sides over the scope of Israeli troops
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side insisted that Israel accept a
U.S. initiative over the redeployment, which calls on Israel to
hand over 13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
But Israel wanted to make a change in the formula, proposing a
handback of 10 percent, with the other 3 percent turned into a
"nature reserve," in which the Palestinians are not allowed to
build new houses and even free access.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians rejected the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said "the Israeli ideas are outside the terms of
references for signed agreements or even for the U.S. initiative."
</P>
<P>
"On its part, the Palestinian leaership refused these ideas
since they are neither new nor serious," he said.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said Palestinian National Authority President Yasser
Arafat exchanged three letters with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright over the past three days to discuss the current
direct talks.
</P>
<P>
In his letters, Arafat briefed Albright on the outcome of the
lastest peace talks, saying Israel did not present any new ideas
on the redeployment and demanding the U.S. publicize its
initiative, Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
Washington has so far not publicized the initiative due to
Israel's insistence.
</P>
<P>
In the letters, Arafat also reiterated the commitment of the
Palestinian leadership to the U.S. initiative and to the sincere
and faithful implementation of signed agreements, he added.
</P>
<P>
In her replies, Erekat said, Albright still urged the two sides
to maintain direct talks, saying there is still hope. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
