<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Bomb Found in Hijacked Russian Airliner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 9 (Xinhua) -- No explosives were found on a
Russian TU-154 aircraft hijacked Sunday with 97 passengers on
board, the Interior Ministry department based in the local
Domodedovo airport said.
</P>
<P>
All the passengers who took the Irkutsk-Tyumen-Moscow flight
are now out of danger in the airport's VIP lounge, the Interfax
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This contradicts an earlier report by the airport's security
chief, quoted by Interfax, that terrorists were still holding 70
people hostage on board the plane.
</P>
<P>
The FSB's special Alfa commando, and units from the Interior
Ministry, the Air Force and the Ministry for Emergency Situations
have left the airport, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Federal Security Service (FSB) servicemen, however, are
searching and questioning the passengers to identify the author of
hand-written note that threatened to blow up the aircraft unless
100,000 U.S. dollars was provided.
</P>
<P>
The handwriting of each passenger is being compared with the
note to trace down the terrorist who is obviously among the
passengers.
</P>
<P>
It was initially reported that only one man hijacked the plane,
but the FSB said later there might be two terrorists aboard.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted airport management as saying that the
situation is under control and the airport continues to operate as
usual. 
</P>
</TEXT>
