<HEADLINE> Annan Condoles With Kenya Over Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 9 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Sunday sent a letter of condolence to victims of Friday's
bomb blast in Kenyan capital, reported the state-run Kenya News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Annan said he was shocked by the bomb raid
aimed at the U.S. embassy in downtown Nairobi. The blast killed
at least 155 people and injured nearly 5,000.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the United Nations will provide assistance to help
the east African country deal with the tragedy, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has also received condolences from Britain's Queen
Elizabeth II and Australian Prime Minister John Howard.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued from the presidential office
Saturday, Queen Elizabeth II has, through Kenyan President Daniel
arap Moi, sent a message of sympathy to the bereaved families and
those injured following the bomb explosion in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
In a similar message to the Kenyan government, Australian
Prime Minister John Howard said: " He and Australians were
shocked by the news of the terrorist attack." He said that
terrorism was cowardly and indiscriminate in its consequences.
</P>
<P>
