<HEADLINE> Kuwait Concerned About U.N.-Iraq New Standoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait expressed concern
Sunday over the latest crisis between Iraq and the United Nations
triggered by Iraq's suspension of cooperation with U.N. weapons
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
This was Kuwait's first official reaction to the new
development, which was made during a weekly cabinet session.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's Interior Minister and acting Minister of State for
Cabinet Affairs, Mohammad Khaled Al-Sabah said after the
session that the council of ministers regarded the Iraqi move as a
violation to the U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi move threatened the region's security and stability,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti government called on the international community to
press the Iraqi regime to bring about its compliance with the
U.N. resolutions, Al-Sabah said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced last Wednesday that it would suspend
cooperation with the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on disarming
Iraq of the weapons of mass destruction and the International
Atomic Energy Agency unless the U.N. lifts the sanctions imposed
on Iraq after the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq adopted the move after the talks on weapons inspections
between Iraq's Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz and UNSCOM chief
Richard Butler broke down last Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
