<HEADLINE> Palestinian Legislators Approve New PNA Cabinet  (by Tan Xinmu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Despite dissatisfaction of
some of its members, the Palestinian Legislative Council (PLC)
voted Sunday to approve the new cabinet of the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
In the West Bank city of Ramallah, the 88-seat PLC endorsed
with a vote of 55-28 the lineup of the PNA cabinet presented last
week by PNA President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The vote had been scheduled for Saturday, but was delayed at
the request of 30 PLC members who wanted to address the
legislature regarding the new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet reshuffle, that had been delayed for about one
year, sparked strong criticism from some PLC members who noted
that most of the ministers accused of corruption retained their
seats in the new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
It was the charges of corruption and mismanagement that led to
the demand by the PLC for the latest cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Arafat appointed 10 new ministers to the old 18-member cabinet,
most of whom come from the mainstream Fatah faction led by Arafat.
</P>
<P>
In a sign of rebuke to Arafat, Hanan Ashrawi, one of prominent
Palestinian political figures on the international stage,
announced resignation Thursday from the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi rejected the offer of being transferred to another post
in the cabinet, charging Arafat for failing to tackle the
widely-reported corruption and mismanagement of the peace talks
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Another minister Abdul Jawad Salah also resigned the same day
to protest what he termed the Palestinian leader's failure to
deal with the internal problems of the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi was transferred from the Higher Education Ministry to
the Tourism Ministry in the reshuffle, while Salah, who was
Agriculture Minister, was made a minister without portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, Arafat convened several meetings of the Fatah
bloc in the PLC to coordinate their positions on Sunday's vote.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Fatah legislators to vote for the new cabinet so
that the Palestinians could proceed with what he described as
their most important challenge - the establishment of an
independent Palestinian state next May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
