<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Want Resident Participation in Urban Planning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Several young Chinese scientists
today advised city dwellers to participate in urban planning for
the next century as part of a strategy for sustainable development
long advocated by Chinese leaders.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 urban planning specialists exchanged views on
urban sustainable development at a forum for young scientists here
today sponsored by the China Association of Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
Some of the participants pointed out that urban plans
should be made not only by government and experts, but also by
the city residents themselves.
</P>
<P>
"Residents' life demand should be taken into account when
making city plans. Residents have the biggest say whether a city
has vigor, and whether it is sustainable," said Wu Chengzhao of
the College of Architecture and Planning at Tongji University in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Wu said some cities are densely populated and constructed
monotonously with little greenery and space set aside for outdoor
activities, a potentially unhealthy situation.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than 50 percent of young Chinese
urbanites are dissatisfied their leisure time, and over 700,000
residents of Shanghai, China's largest commercial city, suffered
from depression in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"Planning a sustainable city needs the views of people from all
walks of life, including experts, and scientific and rational
design, as well perceptive suggestions from the residents," said
Doctor Gong Jianhua of the Department of Geography at the Chinese
University of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Gong is trying to design a future Hong Kong, using computer
virtual reality technology, in order to help Hong Kong residents
make suggestions about the city's future construction plans.
</P>
<P>
He said that residents will be able to enter into the virtual
Hong Kong through the Internet. In the virtual Hong Kong,
scientific concepts of ecology and sustainability have been
translated into models. Residents may judge whether a plot of
grass, a building, or a street is acceptable. Then experts and
policy-makers will receive the suggestions via computer.
</P>
<P>
Gong said he once was surprised by a slogan about sustainable
development in a remote Chinese village. "No matter how much the
villagers understand about sustainable development, the concept
has been widely spread in China."
</P>
<P>
Gong said he has great confidence that Chinese residents will
help engage in urban planning in the next century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
