<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More South Korean Firms Trying to Avoid Layoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 9 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of South
Korean companies are trying to avoid laying off its workers by
reducing working hours, stopping production temporarily and
retraining redundant workers, a survey released by the Labor
Ministry Sunday said.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, such measures helped some
242,000 workers keep their jobs.
</P>
<P>
The number of companies now trying to avoid layoffs marked a
four-fold rise last month from the average number in the first six
months of the year, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a monthly average of 257 companies received
government assistance for taking measures to avoided layoffs.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government provides financial assistance to
ailing companies which promised not to lay off workers in a bid to
reduce unemployment since the nation started suffering a financial
crisis triggered by corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of
financial institutions late last year.
</P>
<P>
The number of firms receiving financial assistance from the
government to avoid layoffs hit 1,045 last month.
</P>
<P>
Companies which do not fire workers are given enough funds to
train them for six months.
</P>
<P>
For small and medium-sized companies, the amount of financial
aid is equivalent to two thirds of wages paid to an employee
during the employment maintenance period. For large companies,
the aid amount is one half of the wage.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, some 82 percent of managers and
workers have agreed to take pay cuts or wage freezes for this year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July this year, a total of 3,337 companies
concluded their annual wage negotiations with labor unions,
according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Among them, 2,738 firms reached deals with labor unions,
agreeing to pay reductions or wage freezes, while only 18 percent
of the total decided to raise wages.
</P>
<P>
Layoffs are new to South Korean workers, who are used to a
guarantee of life-long employment after layoffs were legalized in
February this year.
</P>
<P>
The nation's unemployment rate shot up to 7 percent last month
with more than 1.5 million people jobless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
