<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 49,000 Held in Nigerian Prisons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 9 (Xinhua) -- A total of 49,000 inmates, made up
of convicts and those awaiting trials are being held in prisons
across Nigeria, Nigeria's prison authority said.
</P>
<P>
According to Alhaji Ibrahim Mohammed Jarma, the Comptroller-General
of Prisons, the capacity of the prisons in Nigeria is for 28,000
prisons.
</P>
<P>
Besides congestions, he said, the prisons also lacked
workshops for training inmates with a view to reforming them for
a gainful livelihood at the end of their terms of imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
As a result, he said, ex-convicts were rejected by the society
and they always went back to crime and eventually into prison.
</P>
<P>
Jarma further disclosed that few training workshops have been
converted into prison cells to create space for the ever growing
number of inmates, the official New Nigerian reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to expand the present capacity of the
prisons.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the newspaper said a training workshop
on human rights and prison systems in Nigeria will be held from
August 11 to 13 in Kaduna State, in north Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The workshop will be jointly organized by the National Human
Rights Commission, the International Committee of Red Cross and
the Nigerian Prison Services, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
