<DOCNO> XIE19980809.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Exports Expected to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The economic research institutes of
South Korean family-owned conglomerates, or chaebols, predicted
that the nation's exports will fall roughly 10 percent in the
second half of this year from last year.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, they said the current account surplus will
drop from 22.4 billion U.S. dollars in the first half of this year
to some 20 billion U.S. dollars in the second half.
</P>
<P>
They attributed the gloomy exports prospects to rising value of
the won against the greenback, the weakening Japanese yen, growing
worries over the U.S. economy, and economic setbacks in most
Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
In exports, South Korea registered a drop of three percent in
May, 5.6 percent in June, and 13.9 percent in July this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports saw persistent decreases of 35.9 percent in
March, 37.6 percent in May, 36.6 percent in June and 43.7 percent
in July.
</P>
<P>
Alarmed by the plunges both in exports and imports, the
economic research institutes have readjusted or are redressing
their forecasts for the Korean economy in the latter half.
</P>
<P>
The Daewoo Economic Research Institute has made a downward
adjustment of its original forecasts for exports in the second
half from the original 71.1 billion U.S. dollars to 62.9 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Korea is expected to see both exports and imports decline
significantly in the second half because of serious credit crunch
stemming from financial and corporate restructuring, said the
Daewoo institute.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai Research Institute, which earlier predicted that
exports would reach 67.8 billion U.S. dollars for the second six
months of this year, changed the figure to 66.5 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
LG Economic Research Institute forecast that Korea will see a
trade surplus of 17.9 billion U.S. dollar in the latter half of
1998 with exports of 70.6 billion U.S. dollars against imports of
52.7 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
As the U.S. economy retracts by 1.4 percent in the second half
and the overall world economy is likely to continue suffering from
a slump, it would be very difficult for Korea to regain its
targeted exports in the latter half, said the LG institute.
</P>
<P>
Samsung is considering making a downward adjustment of the
exports and imports figures in the second half after taking into
consideration the weakening yen.
</P>
<P>
The Korea International Trade Association (KITA) predicted that
South Korea will register a trade surplus of 20 billion U.S.
dollars in the second half of this year with exports of 68.4
billion U.S. against imports of 48.4 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
