<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Condemns Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi, looking sad and shaken, toured the bomb rubble in downtown
Nairobi Sunday, mourning for thousands of victims and condemning
the cool-blooded bombers.
</P>
<P>
Latest official figure put the death toll at 155 with
another 4,824 injured in Friday's car bomb raid aimed to the U.S.
embassy located in a very busy commercial area in the Kenyan
capital.
</P>
<P>
The bombing was "astonishing and very terrible," said Moi,
adding that he does not believe the raid would help anyone's cause.
</P>
<P>
"How can they expect Kenyans to support their cause? How can
they expect us to support their cause if they use such methods?"
he asked in a sad mood.
</P>
<P>
"Even if they wanted the U.S. embassy, they should not have
targeted Kenya. Kenyans are peaceful people. Human lives are
precious, it is terrible to use methods that destroy human
beings, innocent human beings," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He urged the public to "be calm and help those in need."
</P>
<P>
"We are pursuing several clues," said Moi, withholding
details.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday night, the Kenyan government said in a statement
that it has taken measures to boost security in all diplomatic
areas, airports, ports and other entrances of the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
The government has also allocated 50 million Shillings (some
850,000 U.S. Dollars) as an emergency fund for the tragedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
