<HEADLINE> Airport Official: 70 Still Held Hostage on Board Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Terrorists held 79 people hostage
on board a passenger plane in the local Domodedovo airport, the
Interfax news agency quoted the airport's security chief as saying
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This contradicted earlier reports that all 94 passengers aboard
the TU-154 plane have been released after negotiations between a
representative of the Russian Federal Security Service (FSB) and
the hijackers. They demanded 100,000 U.S. dollars in ransom and
sought to refuel the plane and fly to an unspecified foreign
country.
</P>
<P>
In a hand-written note, an unidentified man threatened to blow
up the plane if his demands were not met, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which arrived from the Siberian city of Ust-Ilimsk,
was placed on the most remote section of the tarmac of the local
Domodedovo airport.
</P>
<P>
It was initially reported that only one man hijacked the plane,
but the FSB said later there might be two terrorists aboard.
</P>
<P>
The FSB's special Alfa commando, and units from the Interior
Ministry, the Air Force and the Ministry for Emergency Situations
were dispatched to the airport.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted airport management as saying that the
situation is under control and the airport continues to operate as
usual. 
</P>
</TEXT>
