<HEADLINE> 10 Found Dead in US Embassy Bombing in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Ten have been confirmed
dead in the bombing of the United States embassy in Tanzania,
hospital sources said.
</P>
<P>
Reliable sources at the Muhimbili Medical Center (MMC), where
most of the patients were admitted, told Xinhua on Sunday that
all of the dead were Tanzanians, including nine men and one
woman.
</P>
<P>
The sources said most of the dead were the embassy's security
guards, belonging to the Ultimate Security Group.
</P>
<P>
The hospital has reported 63 cases of casualties related to
the bombing, including the dead. Most of the injured admitted to
the hospital have been treated and discharged. Some patients have
been transferred to other hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar President Salmin Amour inspected the MMC on Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Other people injured in the incident have been sent to the
U.N. Dispensary, Mikocheni, Aga Khan and other hospitals, which
have not reported any deaths related to the bombing happened on
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzania Red Cross Society information officer, Ubwa
Suleiman, said it is difficult to count the total number of
injured in the incident, because the hospitals did not deliver
any reports to the society. In addition, he said, some of the
wounded people went home after treatment.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye is expected to visit
the MMC later on Sunday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
