<HEADLINE> All Passengers Released Form Hijacked Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 9 (Xinhua) -- All 97 passengers of the TU-154
plane that was hijacked earlier Sunday in Moscow's Domodedovo
airport have been released, the Interfax news agency quoted Moscow
authorities as saying.
</P>
<P>
The release came after negotiations between a representative of
the Russian Federal Security Service (FSB) and the hijackers who
demanded 100,000 U.S. dollars in ransom and sought to refuel the
plane and fly to an unspecified foreign country.
</P>
<P>
In a hand-written note, an unidentified hijacker threatened to
blow up the plane if his demands were not met, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which arrived from the Siberian city of Ust-Ilimsk,
was placed on the most remote section of the tarmac of the local
Domodedovo airport.
</P>
<P>
After the passengers were led out of the plane, checks began on
their luggage for the presence of weapons or explosives.
</P>
<P>
However, authorities said that the threat to explode the plane
was mere bluff and that no weapons or explosives would be found.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the handwriting of each passenger is being
compared with the note to trace down the terrorist who is
obviously believed to be among the passengers.
</P>
<P>
It was earlier reported that only one man hijacked the plane,
but the FSB now suspects that there might be two terrorists
aboard, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
FSB's special Alfa commando, and units from the Interior
Ministry, the Air Force and the Ministry for Emergency Situations
were dispatched to the airport.
</P>
<P>
