<BODY>
<HEADLINE> b d e 2494 China-Hong Kong-Peg Roundup: Determined Hong Kong Able to Defend Peg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stands firm in its
determination and ability to maintain the linked exchange rate
between its currency and the U.S. dollar after witnessing a week
of continuous economic woes.
</P>
<P>
The volatile week started with a poor mid-year report of the
leading blue-chip Hongkong Bank Group, which announced on Monday a
41-percent slump in profits and an eight-fold rise in provisions
for bad debts.
</P>
<P>
The stock market plunged by about 900 points, or 11 percent on
a string of worse-than-expected interim reports by heavyweight
companies, including Hang Seng Bank, Standard Chartered Bank, Hong
Kong's flagship airline Cathay Pacific and the conglomerate Swire
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Speculators were reported to have made a comeback on Wednesday,
selling off Hong Kong dollars in an attempt to break the peg that
links the Hong Kong dollar to the greenback at 7.8 to one.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA), Hong Kong's de facto
central bank, took quick action by buying in undisclosed amounts
of Hong Kong dollars in the currency market, thus aborting the
speculators' attempt. The move, said the authority, was to
purchase Hong Kong dollars for the government treasury which was
short of funds in this period of the year.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang said the Special
Administrative Region (SAR), backed by solid economic
fundamentals, ample reserves and strong support from the Central
People's Government, is capable of defeating speculators' attacks
on the Hong Kong dollar.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa meanwhile reaffirmed the SAR
government's determination to maintain the linked exchange rate
and China's central banker Dai Xianglong reiterated that Beijing
would not devalue the Renminbi.
</P>
<P>
Concerns over the crippling Japanese yen and rumors about a
Renminbi yuan devaluation resurfaced in the week and cast a shadow
over the economic recovery in the region.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, interbank interest rates rose amid the new wave
of speculative raids on the peg, but not as sharply as in the
previous rounds of currency attacks.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Tsang expected the speculative attacks to
continue for as long as the Asian economic crisis remains. He
pointed out that the recovery of Hong Kong partly relies on the
improvement of the situation in the surrounding areas,
particularly in Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
