<HEADLINE> U.S. Willing to Cooperate With Kenya in Probing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. embassy spokesman Bill Barr
said Sunday that the U.S. administration will cooperate with
Kenya in probing Friday's bomb blast which caused over 4,300
casualties in the Kenyan capital.
</P>
<P>
"We (the two countires) will be very cooperative," said Barr.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four experts from the U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation (FBI) are due in Nairobi Sunday afternoon from
Washington for further investigation into the blast in Nairobi,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The bombing claimed about 150 lives including 11 Americans.
and injured more than 4,200 people, 15 of them Americans.
</P>
<P>
One American man is still missing, Barr told Xinhua, adding
that the 15 injured Americans will be sent to Frankfurt, Germany,
Sunday for treatment.
</P>
<P>
So far 21 Kenyans working for the U.S. embassy have been
confirmed dead.
</P>
<P>
A memorial service will be held here later Sunday for those
died in the blast.
</P>
<P>
Some FBI experts already flew into the Kenyan capital from
South Africa Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Kenya Broadcast Corporation (KBC) said that a
group, self-declared the Islamic Army for the Liberation of
Moslem Holysites, had claimed to be responsible for the bomb
attack.  
</P>
