<HEADLINE> URGENT  Air Passengers Taken Hostage in Moscow Freed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 9 (Xinhua) -- All the passengers and crew taken
hostage on a Russian airliner Sunday at Moscow's Domodiedovo
airport have been freed and left the plane, the Federal Security
Service said.
</P>
<P>
Security officers were on board checking passengers' luggage
for a bomb and asking passengers to leave a handwriting for them
to identify who wrote a note demanding for a 100,000 U.S. dollar
ransom.
</P>
<P>
Before the release, a representative of the Russian Federal
Security Service (FSB) negotiated with hijackers who had seized a
TU-154 jet with 97 passengers.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency reported that the hijackers demanded
100,000 U.S. dollars in ransom and sought to refuel the plane and
fly to an unspecified foreign country.
</P>
<P>
The plane, arrived from the Siberian city of Ust-Ilimsk, is now
on the tarmac of the local Domodedovo airport.
</P>
<P>
It was earlier reported that only one man hijacked the plane,
but the FSB now suspects that there were two terrorists aboard,
Interfax news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The hijackers threatened to blow up the plane if their demands
were not met, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted airport management as saying that the
situation is now under control and the airport continues to
operate as usual. 
</P>
</TEXT>
