<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Japanese Foreign Minister (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jiang said that China and Japan, as important countries in the
world, shoulder a major responsibility to maintain peace and
promote development.
</P>
<P>
In this way, the two sides should work together to bring a
peaceful, prosperous and stable world to the new century, Jiang
added.
</P>
<P>
"We are at an important historical point as the 21st century
approaches," said Jiang, noting that while looking back to the
20th century, the world is full of turmoils and changes, and that
the Sino-Japanese relationship has also undergone ups and downs.
</P>
<P>
He said that the invasion of China by the Japanese militarism
in the 1930s and 1940s had brought not only catastrophes to the
Chinese people, but also great sufferings to the Japanese people.
</P>
<P>
Jiang quoted an old Chinese proverb as saying that "history can
be served as a mirror, in which the rise and fall can be seen."
</P>
<P>
"The deepest enlightenment we have obtained is that as long as
we treat history in a right way, we can open up a better future,"
the Chinese president said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that it is imperative to summerize both the
positive and negative experiences of Sino-Japanese ties, and that
on this basis, the two countries will push forward the bilateral
relationship.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that this year is the 20th anniversary of the
signing of the Sino-Japanese Peace and Friendly Treaty, which has
defined all the principles set out in the Sino-Japan Joint
Statement and thus laid a solid political foundation for the
comprehensive development of bilateral relations and embodied the
common aspiration of both the Chinese and Japanese people to
enhance friendship for coming generations.
</P>
<P>
"I look forward to a state visit to Japan this fall," Jiang
said. "And I am willing to engage in a wide range of contacts with
all walks of life in Japan, including the government and the
public, to discuss and set forth the direction of development for
the bilateral relationship in the long run."
</P>
</TEXT>
