<DOCNO> XIE19980809.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Media's Death Reports on Dyke Burst at Jiujiang Untrue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JIUJIANG, August 9 (Xinhua) -- "How come? No one was killed in
the burst so far," said Ma Yongwei, an army officer, ridiculing
reports by a certain foreign media that tens of thousands were
missing and many bodies seen in a burst on the embankment of
the Yangtze River at Jiujiang, in east China's Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
"It is a sheer lie," said an outraged Xinhua reporter who has
been boating around the dyke in the past two days to cover the
rescue operation and kept in touch with the Xinhua Head Office
via a mobile phone. "We are trying our best to make a full
coverage on what is happening here," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese media, including newspapers and televisions, have
been reporting on the wide-spread floods, the worst since 1954, in
the country in an unexpected frank way over the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Jiujiang burst is one of the latest incidents that have
been and will be closely monitored and covered by local media.
</P>
<P>
According to witnesses, a retiree, whose surname is Yu, is the
first to discover the beginning of the incident at around 13:10
on Friday, when water began to flow in through three water-sodden
bursting points on the dyke, each with a diameter of less than 30
cm.
</P>
<P>
The city flood control headquarters received the report about
the burst at 13:35 and experts were sent to detect the holes on
the inner side of the dyke.
</P>
<P>
Ma and his regiment rushed to the scene at 13:38, when the
size of the holes had grown to some 50 cm each.
</P>
<P>
"The people had enough time to flee, if they wanted," said
Ma. However, they were not scared away and fled. They began trying
to plug up the holes in an organized way.
</P>
<P>
The troops and local civilians made first attempts by throwing
100 cotton-stuffed quilts into the holes, but the effort failed
and the holes turned into a 6 m-wide major breach within two hours.
</P>
<P>
Then, the people dumped a truck at 16:30 trying to fill up the
breach, but it failed again. And, the breach went on to reach
35 m wide on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
In the following two days, an 80-m-long barge, loaded with
1,800 tons of coal, seven small boats and thousands of tons of
rock, paddy, soybeans and whatever at hand were put into the
breach. Heavy trucks have been shipping rocks to Jiujiang
from other parts of the province.
</P>
<P>
"It is very difficult to plug up the burst, due to the
torrential water and a lack of experience, technology and
materials," said the army officer, who has been combating the
burst over the past 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
A local expert told Xinhua that even if the 35 m-breach took
shape in a twinkle, it could not cause deaths. "This is because
the water level of the river stands merely two meters taller than
the ground and the water flow is some 100 cubic meters per
second. In the first hours, the water would be no more than an
ankle's height in the nearby area," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Upon receiving the burst report, the local government began to
ask residents living close to the dyke to move to safe areas
through radio broadcasts and loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
The burst has been attributed to the sustained high water level
in the river as rampant floods, the worst since 1954, has kept
surging in the Yangtze River Basin.
</P>
<P>
"There have been no reported casualties so far in the breach,"
confirmed Governor Shu Shengyou on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In latest developments, a team of army experts have been
summoned in from Hebei Province, north China, to help Jiujiang
plug up the breach.
</P>
<P>
The army experts have decided to hammer in dozens of steel
pipes in three rows on the basement of the breached dyke, while a
90 m-cofferdam has been built next to the breach to slow the flow
of the raging floodwater.
</P>
<P>
"The previous dumping of boats and other materials has slowed
down the water flow by one third and laid a good foundation for
our operation," said an army experts.
</P>
<P>
People have built a second cofferdam to prevent a four
sq. km. flooded urban area in the western part of the
city from further expanding. Currently, a third cofferdam, 3,000
m long, is being built to protect the eastern part of the city.
</P>
<P>
In the past two days, thousands of local residents have been
resettled and the city government has asked those living on floor
to move to higher floors.
</P>
<P>
So far, supplies of running water, electricity and daily
necessities as well as telecommunication services have been
adequate as usual in the city.
</P>
<P>
The city proper of Jiujiang, an industrial center and tourist
attraction in the middle reaches of the Yangtze with an
urban population of about 500,000, has an area of about 30 sq km.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
