<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, August 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's Foreign Ministry on Saturday summoned Pakistani
Ambassador to Iran Javid Husain to condemn the Afghan Taliban
militia for capturing 11 Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan, Tehran
radio reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The summon came after reports said that the Taliban forces
took over the Iranian consulate and captured its staff in Mazari
Sharif on Saturday following their conquer of the city, the main
stronghold of the Northern Alliance headed by the ousted President
Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Iran's special envoy on Afghan affairs Alaeddin Boroujerdi
said the Pakistani government and the Taliban officials should be
responsible for the safety and security of the Iranian diplomats.
(Iran-Taliban-Condemnation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The Contact Group on the former Yugoslavia has
submitted to the Yugoslav government and ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo a document, spelling out autonomy instead of independence
for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The document on a peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis was
revealed by Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Nikolai Afanasyevsky,
the newspaper Politika reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It proposed that Kosovo, under the principle of territorial
integrity of Yugoslavia, could enjoy certain autonomy, but ruled
out any possibility of independence of Kosovo.
(Yugoslavia-Kosovo-Contact Group)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair Saturday condemned
the terrorist attacks on the U.S. embassies in Nairobi and Dar es
Salaam.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the press, the prime minister, who is on
vocation in Florence, said the two bombings should be denounced by
all democratic forces in the world. He also extended his sympathy
and sorrow to the victims' families. (Britain-Blair-Bombings)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The Attorney General's Office has rejected a
U.S. proposal to carry out joint patrolling in Costa Rican waters,
Public Security Minister Roman Solis said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, "the nation," Saturday quoted Solis as saying
the Attorney General's Office will announce this decision next
week.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made one day after U.S. ambassador in Costa
Rica, Thomas Dodd, proposed a new plan for establishing a
mechanism of joint patrolling in Costa Rican waters to combat
drug-trafficking. Solis said the the proposal violates the Costa
Rican Constitution. (Costa Rica-US-Patrolling)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said Sunday that
Japan "strongly urges both the Indian and Pakistani governments to
immediately stop nuclear tests and unconditionally conclude the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty," the Kyodo News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an annual Peace Memorial Ceremony in Nagasaki
marking the 53rd anniversary of the city's atomic bombing, Obuchi
said, "It is extremely deplorable that India and Pakistan
conducted nuclear tests in May this year."
</P>
<P>
He added that his government strongly urges the two South Asian
nations "to stop the development of nuclear weapons and their
missile delivery systems and to unconditionally conclude the
Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty." (Japan-India-Pakistan)
</P>
