<HEADLINE> Zambia Lifts Flour Imports Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Under the pressure from the World
bank, the Zambian government will lift on Sunday its embargo on
flour importation imposed two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Minister of Commerce, Trade and Industry, Enoch
Kavindele, said Saturday that the lifting of the ban, which he
described as "a painful decision", comes into effect from Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the speech in Ndola, 330 kilometers north of
Lusaka, to a large group of farmers drawn from all over Zambia.
He said that the Zambian government is in a difficult situation
since the move has been forced on it by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the lifting of flour imports ban is another
condition made by the western donors.
</P>
<P>
"The government is in a difficult situation of whether to lift
the ban on finished flour imports from abroad and risk cash from
donors or to go ahead and be able to receive cash support from
the Paris Club, " said Kavindele.
</P>
<P>
To resist the lifting of the ban urged by western donors could
protect local wheat farmers but it will be catastrophic to both
individual businessmen and local manufacturing industries since
Zambia depends on donor cash flow, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He further explained that the World Bank has kept pressure on
Zambia since the ban was effected and now it said that apart from
the sale of the mines, Zambia should allow businessmen to bring
the commodity into Zambia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
