<HEADLINE> Water Level Climbing in Wuhan City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The water level in Wuhan, capital
of central China's Hubei province, is slowly climbing as the
fourth flood crest on the Yangtze River, which passed Shashi and
Shishou cities on Saturday, is approaching.
</P>
<P>
It reached 29.34 m at 12:00 today, 0.08 m higher than yesterday's
level, and 0.39 m lower than the 1954 record in 1954, according to
the latest report from the State Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
At that time, water level at Jianli and Luoshan cities upstream
from Wuhan hit 38.16 m and 34.61 m, surpassing the record hights by
0.43 m and 1.1 m, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Due to increasing water flow from upstream, Chenglingji
hydrological station on Dongting Lake recorded a water level of
35.57 m at 12:00 today, 3 cm more than yesterday or 0.26 m more than
the record high.
</P>
<P>
Poyang Lake recorded a water level of 22.29 m, dropping by
three cm than yesterday, or 0.49 m more than the historical record
high.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the water levels in northeast China's Nenjiang
and Songhua rivers have continued to rise. At 12:00 today, Qiqihar
city on the Nenjiang River recorded a water level of 141.38 m,
setting a new recod this year, with the flow rate reaching 9,780
cubic meters per second. 
</P>
</TEXT>
