<HEADLINE> Philippine Students to Get Free Measles Vaccination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Some 17 million students of both
public and private schools in the Philippines will be vaccinated
for free against measles under a 10-year government program, the
education department said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a report to President Joseph Estrada, Education Secretary
Andrew Gonzales said the program is designed to eradicate the
disease, one of the leading causes of death in the country, by the
year 2008.
</P>
<P>
He said the program will start this year and benefit students
in the six to 15 age bracket who are considered at the greatest
risk of contracting the disease.
</P>
<P>
The government will undertake the school-based immunization of
elementary and high school students from September 16 to October
14 while children from nine months to less than five years old
will be vaccinated at vaccination centers, Gonzales said.
</P>
<P>
He said the next target of immunization will be college
students and soldiers who are also at risk of getting measles
since they are exposed to the disease during their frequent
travels.
</P>
<P>
According to the Department of Health, 15 to 20 percent of
children in the Philippines miss their measles vaccination in
their infancy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
