<HEADLINE> Kabila Optimistic Over Solution of Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 9 (Xinhua) -- President of the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) Laurent Kabila Saturday expressed
optimism that a four-member committee of southern African nations
will come up with a solution to the rising tension between his
country and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Mail newspaper, Kabila said relations
with the Kigali government were deteriorating and an urgent
solution had to be sought for a "serious crisis" in the Great
Lakes region to be avoided, Sunday Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
The four-member committee was constituted at the summit which
was held in Victoria Falls Town of Zimbabwe and attended by seven
leaders from southern African nations to seek a solution to the
DRC crisis.
</P>
<P>
President Kabila came to the summit with some demands, one of
them being the immediate withdrawal of Rwandan troops alleged to
have invaded DRC.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda has denied that it has troops fighting alongside rebels
in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
His other demand was for the meeting to issue a statement
condemning without reservation the invasion of the DRC by Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The seven leaders could not deliver such a statement given
that Rwandese President Pasteur Bizimungu denied the alleged
invasion. the committee will investigate the allegations.
</P>
<P>
"I hope they (the committee) will decide soon what to do with
our demands. The situation is really tense. There is an
aggression with Kigali. Relations are not good at all, but I am
sure we can ameliorate our relations," Kabila said.
</P>
<P>
He said his country has scheduled elections for next year and
a constitutional assembly is expected to be in place in the next
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
"Our people are with us and we have the capacity to mobilize
them to defend their sovereignty," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
