<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Urges India, Pakistan to Stop Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi said Sunday that Japan "strongly urges both the Indian and
Pakistani governments to immediately stop nuclear tests and
unconditionally conclude the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty," the
Kyodo News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an annual Peace Memorial Ceremony in Nagasaki
marking the 53rd anniversary of the city's atomic bombing, Obuchi
said, "It is extremely deplorable that India and Pakistan
conducted nuclear tests in May this year."
</P>
<P>
He added that his government strongly urges the two South Asian
nations "to stop the development of nuclear weapons and their
missile delivery systems and to unconditionally conclude the
Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty."
</P>
<P>
Obuchi vowed that Japan would continue adhering to and
strengthening the nuclear nonproliferation regime.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, Nagasaki Mayor Itcho Ito delivered a peace
declaration urging the Japanese government "to pursue true
security independent of the 'nuclear umbrella'" provided by the
U.S. nuclear capability.
</P>
<P>
The declaration also urged the Japanese government to enact
into legislation Japan's three principles of not producing,
possessing, or bringing into the country nuclear weapons, and to
make efforts to turn northeast Asia into a nuclear-free zone.
</P>
<P>
Ito also presented a list of 3,186 new atomic bomb victims,
bringing the total number of deaths from the World War II
U.S. nuclear bombing to 118,855.
</P>
<P>
Some 25,000 people, including survivors of the atomic bombing
and members of bereaved families attended the ceremony at
Nagasaki's Peace Park.
</P>
<P>
Symbolizing a prayer for world peace and a desire to console
war victims, some 450 doves were released after Ito delivered the
peace declaration.
</P>
<P>
At 11:02 a.m., the exact time of the blast 53 years ago,
Nagasaki citizens observed one minute of silent prayer, while
church and Buddhist temple bells sounded throughout the
southwestern Japanese city.
</P>
<P>
The atomic bomb dropped by a U.S. B-29 bomber on August 9, 1945
killed an estimated 74,000 people and injured some 75,000 others
immediately after the attack.
</P>
<P>
The bombing of Nagasaki, three days after that of Hiroshima,
was followed by Japan's unconditional surrender in World War II
six days later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
