<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Petroleum Hamdi Al-Banbi said
that the implementation of three large projects for converting 10
gas discoveries into producing fields is underway, local daily
Al-Ahram reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The investment of the projects located in the western desert
and the northern coast will be 2.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The development of the largest gas discoveries in the deep
waters west of Delta has started with the exploitation of the
latest technology for the first time in Egypt. The other two gas
fields are expected to produce up to 90 million cubic feet of
liquefied gas per day.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Eritrea are ready for setting up a maritime
line between them to activate future trade cooperation, Eritrean
Ambassador in Cairo Mohamed Omar Mahmoud said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of this line was the goal of the visit by an
Eritrean ministerial delegation which is visiting Egypt since
Tuesday, said Mahmoud.
</P>
<P>
The delegation groups ministers of trade, industry, energy and
mining who held talks with their Egyptian counterparts on ways of
strengthening cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The volume of Tunisia's cement exports hit 1 million
tonnes in 1997 compared to 796,000 tonnes in 1996, an increase of
25.6 percent, local daily Al-Sabah reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Tunisia's domestic cement sale meanwhile decreased to 237,000
tonnes in 1997 from 314,000 in 1995 and 255,000 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The approved investment in the agriculture and sea
fishing sector in Tunisia reached 112.5 million dinars (97 million
dollars) till the end of June, an increase of 35.4 percent from
the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture and Sea Fishing attributed the
increase to the additional 15.1 million dinars (13 million
dollars) in investment by agriculture development firms.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The number of Tunisian firms involved in the
industrial rehabilitation program was 713 out of which 282 firms
have obtained a final approval from the government.
</P>
<P>
The approved firms received a financial support worth 97.4
million dinars (83.9 million dollars) while the investment in them
reached 744.6 million dinars (641 million dollars), the Ministry
of Industry said Saturday. Tunisia started the ten-year
rehabilitation program which covers 4,000 firms in 1995 to update
these firms and enhance their international competitiveness.
</P>
</TEXT>
