<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Brazil Cracks Down On Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Brazil is stepping up its
fight against rampant smuggling that has drained the state coffers
and posed a threat to the normal market operation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian government, in tightening control over the
seaports, international airports and land borders, has cracked
some 1,000 smuggling cases since late last year, seizing thousands
of tons of smuggled goods.
</P>
<P>
Smugglers, taking advantage of the country's 7,400
kilometer-long coastline and easy access to neighboring countries
across its lengthy border, have made Brazil a heaven for smuggling
in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics showed that in 1997, foreign goods worth 15
billion U.S. dollars were smuggled into Brazil, depriving the
country of 4 billion U.S. Dollars in tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
Smuggled computers, electrical home appliances, mobile
telephones, cigarettes, clothes, sports shoes, automobile tyres
and other exotic goods could easily be found in major cities like
Sao Paulo and Rio De Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
On the other side, Brazil's timber, gold, gems and wild animals
were taken out of the country by traffickers.
</P>
<P>
To curb the increasingly rampant smuggling, the tax and police
authorities cracked 700 smuggling cases and intercepted 4,500 tons
of smuggled goods in an operation in Santos, Brazil's import and
export hub.
</P>
<P>
At the international airports of Sao Paulo and Brasilia,
customs officers seized telecommunication products worth tens of
millions of U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In Sao Paulo, the authorities unearthed 45 warehouses where
hundreds of tons of smuggled goods such as electrical products,
information products and sports shoes were seized.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, tax authorities, police and security forces
took joint action in a southern city bordering Paraguay, and
seized 60 tons of smuggled goods.
</P>
<P>
The police intercepted about 40 tons of goods, including
electrical home appliances, cigarettes, foreign-made wine and
information products, after sudden inspections over the trucks on
the highways leading into Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian government is also enforcing discipline on the
country's tax and customs officers, punishing those breaking
regulations and taking bribes. For example, the state authorities
of Sao Paulo fired seven customs employees in one year last year.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the police formed a special unit in charge of
fighting international smuggling.
</P>
<P>
A high-ranking tax official said that tightening controls over
the customs and combating smuggling are to safeguard the country's
sovereignty and dignity, and Brazil will show no mercy to
smugglers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
