<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> County Destroys Dykes to Save Major City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Jianli County, in Hubei Province of
central China, destroyed some secondary dykes at 12:00 today to
divert floodwater to save Wuhan, capital of Hubei.
</P>
<P>
Jianli stands some 150 km upstream from Wuhan. Some 50,000
local residents living in the 180-sq.-km. diversion area have been
resettled.
</P>
<P>
The diversion area could hold 800 million cubic meters of
floodwater. The diversion in Jianli is expected to lower Yangtze
water levels by 10-25 cm on the Yangtze section between the Three
Gorges and Wuhan.
</P>
<P>
County leaders of Jianli offered to give up some of local
dykes on Saturday. But the diversion had not been materialized
immediately until today, because some local villagers were
reluctant to remove. It took local officials some time to persuade
them.
</P>
<P>
The central government has attached top priority to the lives
of the people and ordered that no diversion program could be carried
out without relocating all the affected residents.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government is still pondering on a major
diversion scheme to be carried out by blasting part of the main
dyke of the Yangtze in the Jingjiang Diversion Zone in Gong'an
County, 50 km upstream from Jianli. All the local residents that
would be affected by the proposed diversion have been resettled in
safe places.
</P>
<P>
The flood situation in Hubei has not gotten much better,
though the water level at Shashi has continued to fall, standing
at 44.70 at 12:00 today.
</P>
<P>
The major diversion program would be carried out in the
Jingjiang diversion zone, when the water level at Shashi reaches
45 m. and is still going up. It would mean that a part of
Yangtze's embankments in Gong'an would be dynamited and the North
Flood Gate would be opened to discharge floodwater. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
