<HEADLINE> Iran Summons Pakistani Envoy over Captured Iranian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The summon came after reports said that the Taliban forces
took over the Iranian consulate and captured its staff in Mazari
Sharif on Saturday following their conquer of the city, the main
stronghold of the Northern Alliance headed by the ousted President
Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Iran's special envoy on Afghan affairs Alaeddin Boroujerdi
told Husain that the Pakistani government and the Taliban
officials should be responsible for the safety and security of the
Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Iran calls on Islamabad to take serious measures to release
Iranian diplomats as soon as possible, Boroujerdi said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi
also called on the Pakistani government to help ensure the
safety of Iranian diplomats and their immediate release through
Islamabad's contacts with the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban regime formed in 1996 after defeating the
government troops is recognized and backed by Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi also condemned the continued bloodshed in Afghanistan
and killing of innocent people in northern parts of the war-torn
country.
</P>
<P>
Iran has announced time and again that military force is no
solution to the Afghan crisis and the region is in dire need of
calm and tranquillity, Mohammadi said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that due to considerable foreign interference, the
Afghan crisis has entered a new phase which brings about
further massacre of innocent people and rendering homeless
thousands of people of Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
