<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka's Foreign Exchange Reserve Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's foreign exchange
reserve declined by 7.52 percent to 1.618 billion U.S. dollars by
the end of July from 1.74 billion dollars a month earlier despite
government effort to improve the position of foreign exchange
holdings.
</P>
<P>
The nation's foreign exchange reserve was short of the
appropriate level as recommended by the International Monetary
Fund, which calls on a country to retain foreign currencies
equivalent to three months' import bills, a Finance Ministry
official was quoted Sunday by the national New Nation daily as
saying.
</P>
<P>
For Bangladesh, a reserve of at least 1.95 billion dollars is
considered appropriate as the country's monthly imports usually
amount to 650 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The official predicated a continued depletion of the country's
foreign exchange reserve in the coming months because of growing
import demand and a fall in remittances by Bangladeshi wage
earners abroad.
</P>
<P>
The government's decision on Thursday to import 500,000 tons of
food grain, including 300,000 tons of rice and 200,000 tons of
wheat on an emergency basis to expand the country's stock, put
serious pressure on the foreign exchange reserve level.
</P>
<P>
A high official of the International Division of the Bangladesh
Bank, the country's central bank, attributed the depletion of
foreign exchange reserve to the huge payments for the import of
food grain, industrial raw materials, capital machinery and luxury
goods during the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Reduced export receipts were also responsible for the dip in
the reserve, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
