<HEADLINE> Contact Group Outlines Autonomy for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Contact Group on the former
Yugoslavia has submitted to the Yugoslav government and ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo a document, spelling out autonomy instead of
independence for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The document on a peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis was
revealed by Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Nikolai Afanasyevsky,
the newspaper Politika reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It proposed that Kosovo, under the principle of territorial
integrity of Yugoslavia, could enjoy certain autonomy, but ruled
out any possibility of independence of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister of the Yugoslav Federation Nikola
Sainovic was reported to have expressed satisfaction about the
document while response from the Kosovo side was not yet
available, Afanasyevsky said.
</P>
<P>
Russia had been urging ethnic Albanians to return to the table
of negotiations, he said.
</P>
<P>
British Ambassador in Belgrade Brian Donnelly Saturday
presented the document to Kosovo's political leader Ibrahim Rugova
during a closed-door meeting in Pristina, Kosovo, the newspaper
Vecernje Novosti reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
