<HEADLINE> Chinese Americans Protest Anti-Chinese Violence in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 1,000 people from the
Chinese community in metropolitan Washington areas rallied
Saturday at the Indonesian Embassy here to protest against the
anti-Chinese violence in Indonesia in May.
</P>
<P>
"Punish raptists!" "Punish murderers!" the protesters shouted
in front of the embassy. "We want justice, we want it now!"
</P>
<P>
During the riots caused by an economic crisis in May, 470 of
the 1,200 people who were killed were Chinese Indonesians, reports
said. At least 168 women and children of Chinese descent were
gang-raped in public.
</P>
<P>
"For the overseas Chinese all over the world, it is extremely
painful to learn about the crimes committed against Chinese
Indonesian women and children," said a protest letter signed by
hundreds of people.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that Indonesia's history shows a clear pattern
of violence against its Chinese minority.
</P>
<P>
"Whenever things got tough ... whenever there was social or
economic turmoil, the floodgate of violence would be opened up and
torrents of hate crimes driven by blatant racism would be directed
against Chinese Indonesians," noted the letter.
</P>
<P>
It demanded the Indonesian government "immediately stop the
on-going violence against the Chinese communities," "bring the
guilty to justice and conduct a thorough and unbiased
investigation."
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government should also apologize to the Chinese
communities and compensate families of the victims, the letter
said.
</P>
<P>
The protesters urged Indonesian authorities to enact new laws
to protect the rights of all minorities in Indonesia and to
prevent the recurrence of such horrible events.
</P>
<P>
The rally, one of a series of protests against the anti-Chinese
violence in Indonesia, was organized by the Indonesia Chinese
Human Rights Defense League, which was set up two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
"Our demonstration today illustrates that Chinese in America,
united, will not stand by in silence until Jakarta redresses these
wrongs and eliminates its apartheid toward the ethnic Chinese,"
said Samuel Mok, a leading member of the League.
</P>
<P>
He said that the tragedy should also serve as a lesson for the
Chinese people around the world.
</P>
<P>
"We Chinese Americans should not limit ourselves to our own
communities. Failure to engage in the mainstream political and
social activities in America can be costly," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rally was also joined by some Americans. Don Stallone, an
American who works with Chinese colleagues, said, "I think what is
happening to the Chinese population in Indonesia is pretty much
equivalent to what Hitler did to the German Jews ... It's
genocide."
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Chinese represent about 3 to 4 percent of Indonesia's
population of 200 million. They have few political rights and
their language and cultural tradition are forbidden in Indonesia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980809.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Ease Key Car Leasing Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 9 (Xinhua) -- People in Thailand may be able to
pay less money in a longer installment period when they lease cars
if the Finance Ministry convinces the central bank to soften the
key regulations for the industry.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post Sunday quoted Deputy Finance Minister Pisit
Lee-artham as saying his ministry will ask the Bank of Thailand,
which governs the leasing industry in the country, to relax two
key regulations for car leasing.
</P>
<P>
The first regulation deals with minimum down payments on
leasing and auto hire-purchase. The ministry wants regulators to
reduce minimum down payment from 25 percent to 10 percent of the
purchase price.
</P>
<P>
The second change is to extend the maximum installment period
from 48 months to 60 months.
</P>
<P>
Both changes are hoped to spur demand in the hard-hit
automobile industry and increase consumer purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
Pisit said auto sales in the first half of this year had fallen
80 percent from the same period last year. Both the auto and
consumer electronics industries have been hard hit by the
recession, as public spending has fallen sharply because of the
economic uncertainty and decline in consumer confidence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
