<HEADLINE> Chinese Aero-Technology Trade Takes off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- China National Aero-Technology
Import &AMP; Export Corp (Catic), the trading arm of Aviation Industries
of China (Avic), achieved 675.5 million U.S. dollars in trade
volume in the first half of this year, well above the expected,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The figure accounts for 50.82 percent of Catic's expected
trade volume for 1998, representing a 14.49 percent increase from
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, export earnings stood at 301.57 million
U.S. dollars, nearly as much as in the first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Imports were valued at 374.03 million U.S. dollars, up 31.73
percent.
</P>
<P>
To explore new markets, Catic organized a demonstration flight
delegation last October to visit Egypt, Kenya, Zimbabwe, Zambia,
Tanzania, Ethiopia and Eritrea. This was the biggest such
promotional exercise in the history of China's aviation industry.
</P>
<P>
Featured in the long-distance demonstration tour were the K-8
trainer aircraft, Y-7 H-500 and Y-7 100.
</P>
<P>
As a result, many contracts subsequently materialized. By the
end of June this year, orders secured for aircraft exports had been
worth 63.8 million U.S. dollars and aircraft delivered had been valued
at 68.04 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
