<HEADLINE> Newpaper Groups Battle for Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Rupert Murdoch's News Corp is
likely to be the model for emerging Chinese newspaper groups,
which are becoming increasingly market-oriented as competition in
the mass media hots up, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
China's first newspaper group, the Guangzhou Daily Group, was
founded in 1996. A further four groups -- the Nanfang Daily, the
Yangcheng Evening News, the Economic Daily and the Guangming
Daily -- were formed in May and June this year.
</P>
<P>
"Formation of newspaper groups will enable the mass media to
adapt better to the market-driven economy. Our goal is to expand
the influence of 'Party' newspaper, and enhance their financial
strength," said Xu Guangchun, deputy chief of the Publicity
Deparment of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of
China, at the opening ceremony for the Economic Daily and the
Guangming Daily groups.
</P>
<P>
The five newspaper groups have all been registered as companies
by the State Industry and Commerce Administration, meaning they
have independent rights to invest in or manage enterprises.
</P>
<P>
China now has 2,160 newspapers and 7,900 periodicals. The total
annual circulation of newspapers in China is estimated at 26
billion copies a year.
</P>
<P>
Information from the State Press and Publications
Administration said China will have eight to 10 newspaper groups
by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
