<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fourth Flood Crest Rushing on Dongting Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The fourth flood crest on the
Yangtze River is rushing on Dongting Lake in central China's
Hunan Province after it passed through Shashi and Shishou cities
of neighboring Hubei Province on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Latest information from the State Flood Control and Drought
Relief Headquarters disclosed that the water level in the main
stream of the Yangtze River from Yichang to Shishou dropped
slowly, while the water level of the Jianli-Hankou section in
Hubei Province has been rising slowly. And the water level
downstream from Wuxue of Hubei has kept stable or receded slowly.
</P>
<P>
By 06:00 hours this morning, the water level monitored at the
Shashi hydrological station went down to 44.74 m, seven cm high
than the past historical high or 0.21 meters lower than
yesterday's level.
</P>
<P>
Water level recorded at Luoshan and Hankou downstream from
Dongting Lake is 34.6 meters and 29.3 meters, respectively, which
have surpassed respective danger lines by 0.43 meters and three
meters. Jiujiang hydrological station recorded a water level of
22.81 meters, almost yesterday's standard.
</P>
<P>
Due to increased water flow from upstream, Chenglingji
hydrological station on Dongting Lake recorded a water level of
35.55 m at 06:00 hours, 3 cm more than yesterday or two cm more
than this year's record high on August 1.
</P>
<P>
Poyang Lake recorded a water level of 22.29 m at 06:00 hours,
one cm drop than yesterday, or 0.5 meters more than the historical
record high by 0.5 meters.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the water levels in northeast China's Nenjiang
and Songhua rivers have continued to rise. At 06:00 hours today,
Jiangqiao hydrological station at the lower reaches of the
Nenjiang River recorded a water level of 141.3 meters, setting a
new recod, while Harbin hydrological station on the Songhua River
monitored a water level of 118.72 meters, 0.62 meters more than
the danger line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
