<HEADLINE> German Clubs Oppose European Super League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Most German soccer clubs are opposed
to the gossiped European Super League reportedly to be held in
2000, a leading club official said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Gerhard Mayer-Vorfelder, president of the Stuttgart club, said
the Super League will pose damages and crises to the national
leagues in Europe, and will result in conflicts between football
associations and investors.
</P>
<P>
"We have set up a committee of professional soccer within the
UEFA and the committee will hold its first session on August 25 to
tackle the issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the private investors are eager to sign contracts in
September with the clubs committed to compete in the Super League,
which will make two German clubs permanent members, namely Munich
and Dortmund.
</P>
<P>
Such a format with 16 permanent members and another 16 seats to
be vied throughout Europe, will enlarge the gap between those
competiting clubs and those outsiders in their respective national
leagues, the german soccer official said.
</P>
<P>
UEFA, the European soccer's governbing body, has reportedly
loosed its stance for a possible compromise settlement with major
European soccer clubs, which will see the eventual kick-off of the
Super League under the auspices of UEFA with large share of
incomes going to competiting clubs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
