<HEADLINE> Overseas Chinese Meet in Budapest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The 6th congress of the European
Federation of Chinese Organizations opened here Saturday with the
attendance of 330 representatives from 105 overseas Chinese
organizations in 21 European countries.
</P>
<P>
Hu Zhiguang, chairman of the 5th congress, made a report on the
federation's work at the opening session.
</P>
<P>
The main themes of the congress this year include integration
of overseas Chinese into the European society, unity among
overseas Chinese, the fight against illegal immigration and
crimes, the stability in the Chinese communities, living
environment for overseas Chinese women in Europe and teaching of
the Chinese language for Chinese children.
</P>
<P>
Liu Zepeng, deputy director of the Office of Overseas Chinese
Affairs under the State Council, Chen Guoyan, Chinese ambassador
to Hungary, Kadar Laszlo, deputy state secretary of the Hungarian
Foreign Ministry, and Szolnoki Andrea, vice mayor of Budapest,
spoke at the session.
</P>
<P>
Kofi Annan, secretary general of the United Nations, sent a
congratulatory letter to the congress, praising the role the
federation has played in promoting peace, understanding,
cooperation and tolerance among the people of different
nationalities.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian President Goncz Arpad said in his message to the
congress that Chinese living in Europe should know clearly their
tasks and seek ways of fulfilling them in order to secure a
prosperous life.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1992 in Amsterdam, the Netherlands, the European
Federation of Chinese Organizations aims to enhance the social
status of the overseas Chinese in Europe and promote unity and
cooperation among themselves. 
</P>
