<HEADLINE> Myanmar Disburses More Loans to Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yangon, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government disbursed a
total of 1.75 billion U.S. dollars in agricultural loans to
farmers in the 1997-98 fiscal year which ended in March,
increasing by 100 million dollars over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total loans, most were used in cultivation of paddy, one
of the four major crops of Myanmar, amounting to 1.34 billion
dollars or 76.8 percent, according to the government's latest
annual report on agriculture.
</P>
<P>
In the fiscal year, the government also disbursed 146 million
dollars in advance payments to farmers who were in financial
difficulties to grow industrial crops such as jute, sugarcane and
tobacco. The move was to enable farmers to grow in time the
seasonal industrial crops which the government needs, thus
benefiting both the state and the farmers.
</P>
<P>
Increased disbursement of loans to farmers is one of the
Myanmar government's main measures for the promotion of
agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the proper measures taken, the country achieved a
growth of 2.9 percent in its gross domestic product in the 1997-98
fiscal year, producing 17.3 million tons of rice in the year.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has set an output target of 18.6 million tons of rice
for the current 1998-99 fiscal year beginning April, which is also
the third fiscal year of the present five-year plan (1996-97 to
2000-2001). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
