<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Exports Up 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai exported 9.43 billion
U.S. dollars worth of goods in the first seven months of this
year, up 10 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In view of the mounting challenge posed by the Asian financial
crisis, the results are better than expected, according to Zhu
Xiaoming, director of the municipal committee for economic
cooperation and foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has set an export volume of 16.3 billion U.S. dollars
this year, an increase of 10.7 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications equipment, electrical appliances, and
machinery all showed rapid growth, while exports of
labor-intensive products like garments, textiles, and iron and
steel were down.
</P>
<P>
Exports to the United States were up 26 percent, to the
European Union, 36 percent; and to Oceania, 19 percent. However,
exports to the Republic of Korea plunged 50 percent, followed by a
12 percent drop in exports to Southeast Asia and 5 percent in
those to Japan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
