<DOCNO> XIE19980809.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Fall of Opposition Stronghold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 9 (Xinhua) -- In another formidable attempt
to take over the whole Afghanistan, the Taliban Saturday overran
Mazar-e-Sharif, the last stronghold of their rival northern
alliance, further dimming the hope of a negotiated settlement to
the Afghan conflict.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, the puritanical Taliban
stormed Mazar-e-Sharif, about 300 kilometers north of the Afghan
capital of Kabul, in an early morning attack and grabbed key
positions in the city Saturday.
</P>
<P>
But analysts here were quick to note that the fall of the
opposition stronghold does not mark the end to the protracted war
in Afghanistan. Instead, the upsurge in fighting may further
undermine the chance for a peaceful solution to the Afghan
imbroglio.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's latest victory came a week after they took
Shiberghan, just 120 kilometers west of Mazar-e-Sharif and the
native stronghold of opposition warlord Rashid Dostum, who is
allied with former Afghan military chief Ahmad Masood and Shiite
Hezb-e-Wadhat.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time in the past year or more that the
turbaned militia have entered the headquarters of the northern
alliance, which has been dogged by frequent bouts of bitter
internecine fighting. The Sunni Taliban forces briefly controlled
Mazar-e-Sharif in May last year with the help of Abdul Malik,
Dostum's former right-hand man. When a deal over power-sharing
fell through, however, Malik staged an about-face and returned to
the opposition ranks, resulting in the militia's disastrous
retreat from the north.
</P>
<P>
With the fall of Mazar-e-Sharif, the Taliban, who now control
more than two-thirds of Afghanistan, have seriously impaired the
morale of the fragile opposition alliance and seem to be in a
better position to complete their four-year campaign to put the
whole country under their strict Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
However, it would be unrealistic to believe that the latest
victory of the hard-line Taliban would help herald some sort of
peace in Afghanistan as the fighting between the warring factions
always follows a see-saw pattern, analysts warned. They noted that
the main forces loyal to Tajik warlord Masood and the Shiite
Hezb-e-Wadhat are actually kept unhurt.
</P>
<P>
It is therefore safe to say at present that it is not the
northern alliance but the international community's peace efforts
that were hit hard by the Taliban's new round of aggressive
assaults as the crucial joint endeavor by Pakistan and Iran for
the restoration of peace in Afghanistan was immediately shelved.
</P>
<P>
Ayaz Wazir, who is in charge of Afghan affairs in the Pakistani
 Foreign Office, and Mohiuddin Najafi, former Iranian ambassador
to Afghanistan, were scheduled to visit Afghanistan for talks with
the leadership of the Taliban and northern alliance.
</P>
<P>
The trip, a follow-up to last month's visits by Pakistani envoy
on Afghanistan Ift Ikhar Murshid to the Taliban's southern
stronghold of Kandahar and by his Iranian counterpart Alaedin
Boroujerdi to the northern alliance's Mazar-e-Sharif, now seems
impossible to materialize.
</P>
<P>
The recent joint initiatives by Pakistan and Iran, both of
which exert strong influence on Afghanistan, were considered of
great significance as the two countries decided to join hands in
finding a solution to the Afghan conflict despite their
differences on Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Pak-Iranian peace initiatives took place at a time when the
Afghan peace process was actually stalemated after the last talks
between the Taliban and the northern alliance collapsed in early
May.
</P>
<P>
The week-long parleys sponsored by the United Nations and the
Organization of the Islamic Conference broke down here on May 3 as
the two sides failed to compromise on the formation of a proposed
Ulema (Islamic scholars) Commission which, if formed, would decide
the future political setup in the war-shattered country.
</P>
<P>
Now the situation has gone from bad to worse as the Afghan
warring factions have apparently abandoned the idea of peaceful
negotiations, leaving little room for maneuver for the
international peace brokers, analysts noted.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban's offensive in the north at this time may also
undermine the newly-established mutual trust between Pakistan and
Iran, which respectively recognize the regime of the Taliban and
the opposition alliance, they said.
</P>
<P>
"The Afghan crisis can be settled only by peaceful means,
through direct negotiations between the Afghan warring factions
under the United Nations auspices," the U.N. Security Council said
in statement on Friday, demanding "an urgent and unconditional
cease-fire leading to a final end to the hostilities."
</P>
<P>
It is self-evident that Afghanistan, a country composed of
multi-ethnic groups, cannot function smoothly under the complete
domination of one particular group even though it might be
militarily the strongest, analysts pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Given the deep division among the Afghan people on the
political, ethnic and tribal lines, lasting peace, which has
eluded the war-torn country for more than two decades, is not
likely to return soon even if all the provinces fall under the
sway of the Taliban militia in the immediate future, they added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980809.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
