<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Wins San Sebastian Cycling Classic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Francesco Casagrande of Italy
savored the biggest victory of his six-year cycling career, by
winning the San Sebastian Classic on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old rider sprinted ahead from Belgium's Axel Merckx
and fellow Italian Leonardo Piepoli after the trio first broke
away 35 kilometers from home.
</P>
<P>
Along the seafront of the Basque city, Casagrande covered the
distance of 232 kilometers in five hours 43 minutes 45 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Merckx, riding for the Polti team, also enjoyed his best ever
result for a secon place finish with Saeco rider Piepoli third.
</P>
<P>
"It all went perfectly to plan. Normally I would have said that
Axel was the better sprinter but in the final kilometers he looked
tired and I knew I had my chance," said Casagrande.
</P>
<P>
The World Cup triumph is his third in the last week following
two victories in his native Italy.
</P>
<P>
Gan-Credit Agricole rider Cedric Vasseur led for much of the
early part of the race and at one stage had more than 11 minutes'
advantage over the main group.
</P>
<P>
A six-man group gradually caught him up by 160 kilometers but
Stephane Petilleau, Fabio Roscioli and Laurent Desbiens all made
short-lived attacks before reaching the final climb.
</P>
<P>
The final 32 kilometers split the field and allowed the leading
trio to escape.
</P>
<P>
Michele Bartoli of Italy finished in the main group but
retained his World Cup lead with six rounds gone.
</P>
<P>
Casagrande moved up 17 places after his victory and now lies
second in the rankings, with four races to go.
</P>
<P>
Tour de France winner Marco Pantani of Italy and second-placed
Jan Ullrich of Germany both made late decisions not to race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
