<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The leading national newspaper runs a special commentator's
article, urging people to take the on-going anti-flood battle as an
overriding task and to adopt effective measures to protect the
embankments along the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
-- Another group of 30,000 officers and men of the PLA (People's
Liberation Army) and the armed police have rushed to major flooded
areas along the Yangtze at the order of the Central Military
Commission.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 100,000 military personnel have been sent to
flood-ravaged provinces in central and east China to join local
militiamen in the fight against heavy flooding.
</P>
<P>
--The fourth flood crest on the Yangtze River passed through
the city of Yichang in Hubei Province early yesterday morning
without causing damages.
</P>
<P>
-- Following the completion and operation of the electrified
project of Beijing-Zhengzhou Railway yesterday morning, China's
operational mileage of electrified railway lines has totalled
11,695 km.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
--China's current period of deflation is not as worrisome as it
seems and may be overcome before the end of this year, Chinese
economists said last week.
</P>
<P>
--China's nationwide concern over macroeconomic performance this
year has turned Chinese economists into the latest stars of the
news media.
</P>
<P>
--Chinese exports to African countries soared in the first half
of this year and the momentum is expected to be maintained for the
next six months, trade experts predict.
</P>
<P>
--China plans to invest around 100 billion yuan to upgrade its
rural power grids over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
"China Youth News"
</P>
<P>
-- Wuhan, capital of Hubei province and also an important city
in central China, is bracing for the pending fourth flood peak by
organizing more members of the Communist Youth League to participate
in the flood combating efforts.
</P>
<P>
The water level at Wuhanguan in Wuhan City monitored at 29.28 m
by 14:00 hours yesterday and is expected to climb to 29.45 today,
which will be 0.28 m lower than the historical high of 29.73 m in
1954.
</P>
<P>
--The second flood peak on the Songhua River approached Harbin,
capital of northeast China's Heilongjiang Province. By 15:00 hours
yesterday, the water level at Harbin rose one cm to reach 118.67
meters. 
</P>
