<HEADLINE> Armed Group Claims Killing of 143 Soldiers in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia (FARC) killed 143 government soldiers and
captured 133 others in an offensive launched this week, the rebel
group claimed in its war report published by the local press
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
About 123 troops were injured in the fighting, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The oldest rebel group in Colombia said that 15 guerrillas died
and 20 were injured in the dozens of attacks waged against
military targets.
</P>
<P>
But the FARC report disagreed with the official figures of
casualties released by the government last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government said 198 rebels were killed and 50 injured,
while 67 military and police personnel lost their lives and 66
others sustained injuries. Ninety-two men were missing in action.
</P>
<P>
The FARC and the National Liberation Army, the second largest
guerrilla group in the country, have said they will hold dialogue
with President Andres Pastrana, who took oath Friday. 
</P>
