<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Rejects U.S. Joint Patrolling Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Attorney General's Office
has rejected a U.S. proposal to carry out joint patrolling in
Costa Rican waters, Public Security Minister Roman Solis said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, "the nation," Saturday quoted Solis as saying
the Attorney General's Office will announce this decision next
week.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made one day after U.S. ambassador in Costa
Rica, Thomas Dodd, proposed a new plan for establishing a
mechanism of joint patrolling in Costa Rican waters to combat
drug-trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Solis said the the proposal violates the Costa Rican
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
The United States hopes that Costa Rica will authorize U.S.
anti-narcotics taskforces to enter Costa Rica's air and sea space
to chase and capture suspicious boats that might be transporting
drugs. 
