<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rice Planting Rushed In Flooded Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Hunan Province in central China
has planted over 1.3 million hectares of late rice so far in spite
of a serious flooding.
</P>
<P>
More than 600,000 hectares of farmland have been destroyed by
flood in Hunan since June. In the city of Changde, which was hit
heavily, people have been trying to make up for the losses by
speeding up the planting of late rice on 82,500 hectares, when the
flood waters began to recede a bit.
</P>
<P>
In Zhangjiajie city, farmers are on alert for possible plant
diseases caused by the flood.
</P>
<P>
Xiangxiang and Liling cities, two major rice producers that
were not affected, are making a greater effort to increase rice
output, using new planting methods.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, farmers in drought-stricken southern part of the
province have intensified efforts to improve the irrigation system
to get the rice in on time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
