<HEADLINE> Export Grows in Southwest China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan Province
exported 530 million U.S. dollars worth of goods from January to
June, up 10.9 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Southeast Asian financial crisis seems to have had little
adverse effect on Yunnan, which borders Viet Nam, Laos, and
Myanmar for more than 4,000 km.
</P>
<P>
Local officials attributed the export growth to the province's
multi-polar market strategy, which has led to a marked increase in
exports to North America and countries other than those in
Southeast Asia, and to the state's preferential policies, such as
a tariff rebate.
</P>
<P>
The province had 840 million U.S. dollars worth of foreign
trade in the first six months, a 3.3 percent increase over the
same period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
