<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boldon Beats Bailey in Golden League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Ato Boldon of Trinidad and Tobago
beat Olympic champion Donovan Bailey of Canada to win the men's
100 meters at the Herculis Golden League athletics meet in Monte
Carlo, Monaco on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Boldon clocked 9.92 seconds to get his revenge against Bailey
who finished second at 9.96, with Frankie Fredericks of Namibia
taking the bronze medal in 10.02.
</P>
<P>
Only world champion Maurice Greene of the United States was
missing from the top field. World-record holder Bailey had won at
Paris July 29, beating Greene and Boldon in 10.02.
</P>
<P>
Boldon has the fastest times of the year, running 9.86 twice,
0.02 seconds short of Bailey's world record in 9.84.
</P>
<P>
"I've been second a few times this year, but every now and then
I run the race I want to win," Boldon said.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 100 meters race, American Marion Jones remained
unbeaten by clocking in 10.72 seconds, only 0.01 second off her
season's world best.
</P>
<P>
A bonus of one million US dollars will be shared among the
athletes who remain unbeaten through the six Golden League meets
and the Grand Prix final at Moscow on September 5.
</P>
<P>
Jones, Ethiopia's Haile Gebrselassie, Nigeria's Charity Opara,
American Bryan Bronson and Morocco's Hicham El Guerrouj are still
alive for the bonus.
</P>
<P>
The next Golden League meet is at Zurich, Switzerland, on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The track is so fast there I think I can beat my personal
best," Jones said. Only American Florence Griffith Joyner has
gone under 10.70, with her world record at 10.49.
</P>
<P>
In other events, Wilson Kipketer opened his season with a
1:43.74 victory in the 800 meters, his first race in nearly 11
months after contracting malaria in January.
</P>
<P>
American Kim Batten ran 52.74, only 0.13 seconds off her world
record and equal to the third-best ever in the women's 400
hurdles, Glory Alozie of Nigeria won the women's 100 hurdles in
12.44, another 1998 best.
</P>
<P>
American Michael Johnson won the men's 400 in 43.96, the second
time he has been under 44 seconds this season, while El Guerrouj
clocked 3:28.37 in winning the 1,500 meters.
</P>
<P>
Gebrselassie captured the 3,000 in an unchallenged 7:25.54.
</P>
<P>
Bernard Barmasai of Kenya took the 3,000 steeplechase in
another season's best with 8:00.67 and Maxim Tarasov of Russia won
the pole vault at 5.90 meters.
</P>
<P>
Bronson won the men's 400 hurdles in 47.93, keeping alive his
Golden League unbeaten record. 
</P>
</TEXT>
