<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, August 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The President of the General Assembly of the
United Nations Hennadiy Udovenko said on Friday that he was
shocked to learn the two bomb explosions in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Udovenko said the blasts were nothing else but
acts of insane and barbarous terror, which cannot be excused or
tolerated. (GA President-Bombs Explosion-Africa)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and French President
Jacques Chirac spoke by phone Saturday about pressing Serb leaders
to stop attacking ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
During a 25-minute discussion, the two presidents talked about
"various ways of keeping pressure on (Yugoslav President Slobodan)
Milosevic to end his offensive and negotiate seriously on a
political resolution," said National Security Council spokesman
P.J. Crowley. (US-France-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- A Kenyan man trapped in the rubble of Friday's bomb
blast got out to safety Saturday night after one and half days of
tense work by rescuers.
</P>
<P>
A huge car bomb explosion brought down the whole building on
the rear of the U.S. embassy, crashing down around the man who is
identified as Gatili Nganga.
</P>
<P>
The man was said at his middle age and was injured quite
seriously. At least one more person was still alive in the
debris. (Kenya-One Alive)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The latest toll in the bomb blast in downtown
Nairobi is 132 people dead, including 11 Americans, and 4,257
injured, a government spokesman said Saturday evening here at a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
At least 11 bodies have been found from the rubble of the bomb
blast since Saturday afternoon, in addition to two retrieved
alive, rescuers told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The rescue workers have managed to continuously communicate by
a microphone with the two trapped people -- one is in a lift,
another one behind a thick concrete wall, Avi Regev, the spokesman
for the Israeli rescue team, said. (Kenya-Blast Toll Figure)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin Saturday resolutely
denied a draft law submitted by the State Duma, the lower house of
parliament, on transferring the president's powers to the prime
minister in case it needs.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, in his message to Duma
speaker Gennady Seleznyov, the president said that the draft law,
"on ensuring the continuity of presidential powers in cases when
Russian president is unable to carry out his duties," is
"conceptually unconstitutional and is not subject to further
consideration." (Russia-Duma-Power Transfer) 
</P>
</TEXT>
