<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Atkinson: Top Players Use Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Former manager Ron Atkinson has
claimed that the Premiership was full of players on cocaine and
cannabis.
</P>
<P>
"I know from my time at Villa that drugs are used by
footballers at the highest level," Atkinson says in his book e
ntitled "A Different Ball Game" serialised by the Mail on Sunday
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Atkinson, in charge at Villa in the early 1990s, said he
subjected the players to blood tests without telling them what
they were for.
</P>
<P>
"When the analysis was completed we discovered that at least
two of Villa's stars of that era had taken an illegal substance."
</P>
<P>
He alleged that drug-taking posed the biggest threat to English
football's future and the biggest drugs dealer in the game was
reputed to be a well-known England international, with a long
Premiership career behind him, who could get "what-ever substance"
players wanted. Premiership players are turning out "with
cocaine, certainly cannabis and all sorts of funy tablets buzzing
around their system".
</P>
<P>
Atkinson, one of the game's most respected figures, said he
first became aware of football's infiltration by drugs at the
start of the decade. And he blames the game's increasing shift
towards a pop star culture.
</P>
<P>
"The really big money was just starting to come into the game
and young lads, no age at all, were having money thrown at them,"
he said. "If they are treated like pop stars, sooner or later they
must start behaving like them."
</P>
<P>
His fears were backed by the FA's medical chief Alan Hodson,
who said: "It will ruin the game if we're not careful."
</P>
<P>
Atkinson added that football's response to its drugs crisis
must be to introduce fortnightly testing for every professional
footballer.
</P>
<P>
Atkinson, sacked last season as manager of Coventry, also said
that in his later management years he considered there to be
"probably a dozen players playing with some sort of illegal
substance in their bodies". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
