<DOCNO> XIE19980809.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Chief Calls to Reduce Drug List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 8 (Xinhua) -- International Olympic Committee
(IOC) president Juan Antonio Samaranch repeated his call on
Saturday to reduce the drug list.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the Catalan regional television station TV3 in
Spain, Samaranch said that he was looking to cut down the number
of banned substances because "it is not a list, it is a book."
</P>
<P>
Samaranch suggested eliminating various medicines which have
ingredients presently banned by the IOC and only retaining on the
proscribed list "those drugs which are really prejudicial to the
health of sports people and which produce artificial results."
</P>
<P>
The IOC president said he hoped that when the IOC executive
committee meets on August 20 it would be able make significant
steps towards convening an IOC-led conference on doping next
January.
</P>
<P>
"We have to define doping in only one way. We must have a
definition that is clear and exact," Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
However the latest statements are believed to bring about
renewed criticism.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch was widely attacked for what was seen as a soft
stance on doping when he recently expressed similar views in the
Spanish newspaper El Mundo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980809.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round the World Balloon Trip Starts in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The aerostatic balloon
piloted by U.S. citizen Steve Fossett left last night from the
city of Mendoza, in the west of Argentina, with the aim of
navigating around the world.
</P>
<P>
As reported today by the local press, the trip will end 18 days
from now with the purpose of breaking all the records in this
matter.
</P>
<P>
Fossett, a U.S. businessman, plans to fly over the Atlantic
Ocean, South Africa, the Indian Ocean, Australia, and the Pacific
and return to South American territory.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. businessman said before leaving that the most
dangerous part of his trip is that he will have to fly over the
oceans of the south of the planet 80 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
The balloon Fossett is flying in is 45.5 meters high, 24.4
meters in diameter, and has inside 2.744 cubic meters of helium
and 2,832 cubic meters of air.
</P>
<P>
The cruising altitude will be 7,300 meters, with a temperature
between 30 and 50 degrees Celsius below zero and an average speed
of 80 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
It was announced that Fossett, who invested 350,000 dollars in
this trip, will receive one million dollars if he completes the
round the world trip in the established time.
</P>
<P>
Fossett has promised that if he gets the million dollars
promised by a brewing firm, he will donate half of it to
Washington University in the city of Saint Louis, where Fossett is
a member of its trust fund board.
</P>
<P>
Fossett, a sportsman, has made several balloon trips. In 1994
he traveled from Canada to Germany, across the Atlantic, and in
1995 flew over the Pacific Ocean. He broke the world record in
1997 when he traveled 9,335 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The first trip in a balloon was made on August 8, 1706, exactly
292 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
